  <Entries>
    <Entry>
      <ID>1</ID>
      <DefaultText>Afternoon sun streams through the balcony doors of a rich library, turning wooden bookshelves and white walls to gold. Books of every kind surround you, leatherbound tomes, Hikarian scent novels, moving picture books, jars of memory ants - all well maintained and neatly ordered. 

Heavy chest-high tables hold more books, and quiet nooks hide oversize chairs. A crimson-furred singing moth trills in a silver cage. 

At a desk, two tall white-haired men of a race you know as the Sona examine what looks like a jade button. 

"The Mindeye it's called," says the older Sona. "A fascinating toy. "Wear it and set it to "See" and it will capture all you experience - every sensation and emotion."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>2</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Place it on someone else and set it to "Show," continues the old Sona, "and they experience everything you captured. A completely immersive experience."

"Remarkable, Lord Veresterios," says the younger sona. "And could you put it on an animal?"

"Certainly," says Veresterios. "A pet, an insect, even an emptyheaded Nil like little Rem here."

He turns and winks at you. "Would you like that Rem? Would you like to view librarian Lanalton's days? Would you like to know what it was like to be a Sona? To be a man? To be able to reach books on high shelves?"

It is then you realize the chairs are not oversize. You are a child sized, blue-skinned, full grown woman - a Nil. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>3</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Yes, sir. Very much."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>4</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell him it would not be fitting for one so lowly to know the thoughts of a Sona. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>5</ID>
      <DefaultText>"No, sir. I would be too afraid."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>6</ID>
      <DefaultText>Veresterios laughs. "I imagine you would! Who'd want the life of a Nil? Always picking up after a bunch of lazy snobs. What do you think, Librarian?"

Lanalton sniffs. "I meant the other way around, sir. Seeing through an animal's eyes, learning how it thinks. If it feels."

"Already done!" cries Veresterios. "I placed the eye on a Nil pot scrubber last week. Fascinating viewing, but dangerous." He pats a book on the desk. "Eosus' diary warns that auditing a mind too different from one's own can drive one mad. One may safely place the device on ones eye to experience just the visual, but more than that..." He shakes his head. "Even within the same race it is not without risk."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>7</ID>
      <DefaultText>Veresterios smiles. "What a well mannered girl you are. Rem. If only all Nil were like you."

Lanalton sniffs and turns from you. "I meant the other way around, sir. Seeing through an animal's eyes, learning how it thinks. If it feels."

"Already done!" cries Veresterios. "I placed the eye on a Nil pot scrubber last week. Fascinating viewing, but dangerous." He pats a book on the desk. "Eosus' diary warns that auditing a mind too different from one's own can drive one mad. One may safely place the device on ones eye to experience just the visual, but more than that..." He shakes his head. "Even within the same race it is not without risk."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>8</ID>
      <DefaultText>Veresterios laughs. "Just like a Nil - unimaginative, frightened of new experiences. That's why your race will never be more than servants."

Lanalton sniffs and turns from you. "I meant the other way around, sir. Seeing through an animal's eyes, learning how it thinks. If it feels."

"Already done!" cries Veresterios. "I placed the eye on a Nil pot scrubber last week. Fascinating viewing, but dangerous." He pats a book on the desk. "Eosus' diary warns that auditing a mind too different from one's own can drive one mad. One may safely place the device on ones eye to experience just the visual, but more than that..." He shakes his head. "Even within the same race it is not without risk."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>9</ID>
      <DefaultText>He locks the Mindeye in a drawer, then stands. "But enough of toys, Lanalton. I require your help. My son, Aurigan is just back from the steadfast, and he has it in his head that he wants to be a Nano. I want you to select some books for him. Come, he's to meet us in my office."

"One moment, my lord," says Lanalton, then turns to you. "You will file all the books on the table before I return." He points to Eosus's diary. "But do n't touch that one. It is worth all the rest combined. I will take care of it personally, understand?"

Before you can reply, he sweeps out after Veresterios and you are alone. The quiet, however, is quickly disturbed. Screams are coming from the balcony. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>10</ID>
      <DefaultText>Looking through the balcony door, you see a massive gray-skinned bodyguard - a Bayan - holding two struggling Nil over the balustrade, dangling them above a kilometer-wide hole so deep you can't see the bottom. Behind him, a handsome young Sona shouts at a third Nil, who kneels in a puddle of water before him, clutching a mop. 

"Murderous pipsqueak," snarls the young Sona. "I nearly fell down the Bore slipping in your slop!"

"I'm sorry, lord Aurigan," says the Nil. "I did put up a rope and a warning si--"

The Sona slaps his face. "Talking back? Just for that, Gurek will drop one of your friends. Quick now, drit. Pick left or right. And if you don't pick, all three of you go over!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>11</ID>
      <DefaultText>Run out and attack Aurigan.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>12</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Don't do it! Spare them!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>13</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stay where you are and do nothing. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>14</ID>
      <DefaultText>Veresterios chuckles. "Too meek to express an opinion? No wonder the Nil never rise. They take whatever we dish out, and ask for seconds."

Lanalton sniffs and turns from you. "I meant the other way around, sir. Seeing through an animal's eyes, learning how it thinks. If it feels."

"Ah, yes," said Veresterios. "Fascinating, but dangerous." He pats a book on the desk. "Eosus' diary warns that auditing a mind too different from one's own can be so jarring as to drive one mad. It is possible to place the device on ones eye to safely experience just the visual component, but more than that..." He shakes his head. "Even between the same race it is not without risk."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>15</ID>
      <DefaultText>Look down shyly and say nothing. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>16</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you race for the young lord, the gray-skinned man throws one of the Nil he's holding at you, and you both go down in a heap. 

The Sona turns on you. "Were you coming for me, girl? Don't you know striking a sona is a capital crime? Gurek, drop that runt over the side, then grab this one. She's next."

Gurek obediently opens his fist and the struggling Nil drops out of sight, shrieking, as the Nil with the mop sobs and clutches the sona's boots. "Please," he says. "No more."

Gurek reaches for you, but as his fingers close around you, Veresterios' voice comes from inside. 

"Aurigan, my boy! Where are you? We're waiting for you!"
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>17</ID>
      <DefaultText>Aurigan turns as you make your plea. 

"Look, Gurek. It's trying to mimic human speech."  He grabs you and pins your arms behind your back, then faces the Nil with the mop. "Now you have three to pick from, drit. Make your choice. Now!"

The Nil looks from you to the two Nil in Gurek's arms. Tears are streaming down his face. "Please, master. I... take me. Let them go and--"

"That wasn't a choice, fool!" snarls Aurigan. "Now--"

But before he can repeat himself, Veresterios' voice comes from inside. 

"Aurigan, my boy! Where are you! We're waiting for you!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>18</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Nil with the mop looks back and forth between the two Nil in Gurek's arms. Tears are streaming down his face. "Please, master. I... take me. Let them go and--"

"That wasn't a choice, fool!" snarls Aurigan, cuffing him over the ear. "Now--"

But before he can repeat himself, Veresterios' voice comes from inside. 

"Aurigan, my boy! Where are you! We're waiting for you!"

The young sona cringes, then shoves you away and beckons to Gurek. "Kill the left hand one. The old man calls."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>19</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Don't do it. I'll tell your father you're killing his servants!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>20</ID>
      <DefaultText>Aurigan laughs as you make your threat. "You think my father cares what happens to livestock?"

He grabs you and pins your arms behind your back, then faces the Nil with the mop. "Now you have three to pick from, drit. Make your choice. Now!"

The Nil looks from you to the two Nil in Gurek's arms. Tears are streaming down his face. "Please, master. I... take me. Let them go and--"

"That wasn't a choice, fool!" snarls Aurigan. "Now--"

But before he can repeat himself, Veresterios' voice comes from inside. 

"Aurigan, my boy! Where are you! We're waiting for you!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>21</ID>
      <DefaultText>The young sona cringes at his father's voice, then beckons to Gurek. "Leave it. The old man calls."

Gurek sets you down and follows his master as the three Nil cluster around you, steadying you. 

"You see, Rem?" says the one with the mop. "He's a monster. He had poor Dal killed for *nothing*. I..." He breaks down again, weeping.

"Coi's right," says the second Nil. "Him and that Bayan of his will kill us all. There's already three maids out with broken arms. And old Jai died of a cracked head last night."

Coi clutches your arm. "You promised you would help us, Rem, so please! You've got more freedom and smarts than any Nil we know. Find some way to... to make him stop."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>22</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I'll keep trying. I promise."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>23</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I don't think I can help you after all."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>24</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I need to think about it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>25</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi takes your hand. "Thank you, Rem. We're relying on you. Thank you. Let us know if you need any help."

The Nil gather up their mops and cleaning rags and leave you alone on the balcony, staring down into the wide hole of the Bore. Had things gone differently, it might have been you who was thrown into it. If you had, you'd still be falling.  </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>26</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi sighs. "I don't blame you for being afraid, but we're doomed without you, Rem. Think about it, all right?"

The Nil gather up their mops and cleaning rags and leave you alone on the balcony, staring down into the wide hole of the Bore. Had things gone differently, it might have been you who was thrown into it. If you had, you'd still be falling.  </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>27</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi nods. "Take all the time you need, Rem. Only... Well, not too long, eh? Only a matter of time before the bastard throws another one of us to our deaths."

The Nil gather up their mops and cleaning rags and leave you alone on the balcony, staring down into the wide hole of the Bore. Had things gone differently, it might have been you who was thrown into it. If you had, you'd still be falling.  </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>28</ID>
      <DefaultText>Returning to the library, you start to put away the books on the table. You don't know the classification system, but it is simple enough, and all the books are in their proper places by the time Lanalton returns. 

He sniffs when he sees that you've finished, as if annoyed that he has no excuse to scold you. "Dust and polish for a while," he says. "Lord Veresterios is reading in his office, and I have work to do."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>29</ID>
      <DefaultText>Talk to Lanalton about Aurigan.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>30</ID>
      <DefaultText>Talk to Veresterios about Aurigan. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>31</ID>
      <DefaultText>Read the Laughing Jack. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>32</ID>
      <DefaultText>Read the Jaws of Victory. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>33</ID>
      <DefaultText>Read Another Man's Mirror. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>34</ID>
      <DefaultText>Work on getting Veresterios to kick Aurigan out of his house. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>35</ID>
      <DefaultText>Work on murdering Aurigan</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>36</ID>
      <DefaultText>Work on making Aurigan a better person. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>37</ID>
      <DefaultText>Read about the Mindeye</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>38</ID>
      <DefaultText>Explore the Library</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>39</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you move around the library with your polishing rag you find, in a closet, three books on a low shelf, stacked beside a Nil-sized cloak. They are; The Laughing Jack - a Romance of Old Sagus Cliffs, The Jaws of Victory - A Memoir of the Endless Battle, and Another Man's Mirror - Lessons in Empathy. Each book has been bookmarked. It seems you have been reading. 

You also notice that Lanalton is so engrossed in his work that he ignores you completely. As long as you keep quiet and out of his line of sight, you can likely do anything - examine the moth, look at the priceless Diary of Eosus and learn more about the Mindeye, or sneak into the closet and read your chosen books. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>40</ID>
      <DefaultText>Look at the Moth</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>41</ID>
      <DefaultText>Decide what to do about Aurigan. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>42</ID>
      <DefaultText>You can think of three ways of dealing with Aurigan - get his father to throw him out, murder him, or try to make him a better person. Alternatively, you could just forget the whole thing and hope for the best. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>43</ID>
      <DefaultText>The librarian sighs as he senses you standing at his shoulder. "Yes? What is it?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>44</ID>
      <DefaultText>You sneak out of the library and knock softly at the open door of Veresterios'  office. He looks up from his desk and smiles. "Yes, girl. What is it? Does Lanalton want me?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>45</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell him that his son nearly killed three of your friends. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>46</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell him that his son endangered his property by dangling his servants off the balcony. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>47</ID>
      <DefaultText>Excuse yourself.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>48</ID>
      <DefaultText>He chuckles. "I think the important word there is 'nearly,' isn't it? Nothing actually happened, eh? Just so."

He turns back to his writing. "I know Aurigan is a bit rough around the edges, my dear, but it's just youthful high spirits. He'll grow out of it. Now run along, won't you? There's a good girl."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>49</ID>
      <DefaultText>He frowns. "Yes. Youthful high spirits can sometimes go too far. Still, your friends weren't actually hurt, were they? Just so."

He turns back to his writing. "If it happens again, I'll talk to him. But let's leave it for now, shall we? I'm sure he'll get bored of such foolishness soon enough. Now run along, won't you? There's a good girl."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>50</ID>
      <DefaultText>A passage on the bookmarked page has been set off with faint pencil marks. It reads:</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>51</ID>
      <DefaultText>He looks up again, eyes sharp this time. "You are making demands of me? I consider myself a very lenient employer, my dear, but I will not be spoken to in that manner by a servant. Go tell Lanalton that he must find a new assistant. You no longer work in my house. Good day."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>52</ID>
      <DefaultText>He looks up again, eyes sharp this time. "You would blame me for the foolishness of my servants? If your friends wish to be left in peace, they should endevour not to anger my son. Just as you should not have angered *me*."

He looks away from you. "Go tell Lanalton that he must find a new assistant. You no longer work in my house. Good day."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>53</ID>
      <DefaultText>He waves, only half listening. "Yes yes. Carry on."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>54</ID>
      <DefaultText>Insist that he talk to son. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>55</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell him that if any Nil die it will be his fault. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>56</ID>
      <DefaultText>Agree with him and leave. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>57</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you walk from Veresterios' office, the wood paneled hallway blurs into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>58</ID>
      <DefaultText>A line has been drawn next to a few paragraphs on the bookmarked page. They read:</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>59</ID>
      <DefaultText>A short section of the bookmarked page has been bracketed with faint lines. It reads:</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>60</ID>
      <DefaultText>Skimming the book you learn how to operate the Mindeye, including how to speed it up so that a day's experience can be viewed in a single hour, or a week's in one night. 

You also learn some of the dangers of using the device, and how to mitigate them, including this:

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>61</ID>
      <DefaultText>The fist-sized moth chirrups and flutters at you as you approach. It is a beautiful thing from afar, with its crimson coat and beautiful wing markings, but it's face is a bit unnerving. It has six eyes, widely spaced so that it can look in all directions at once, and the membrane behind its mandilbles - the organ that allows it to sing - glistens and vibrates in a stomach-churning way. 

If it could talk, it would certainly have a lot to say, for it sees everything that goes on in the library, night and day. 

{SCRIPT: Sets examined the Moth conditional.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>62</ID>
      <DefaultText>Do more research. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>63</ID>
      <DefaultText>Decide to forget the incident. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>64</ID>
      <DefaultText>""</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>65</ID>
      <DefaultText>If Rem read The Laughing Jack

(Slightly different description. Extra choice.)</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>66</ID>
      <DefaultText>If Rem read The Jaws of Victory

(Slightly different description. Extra choice.)</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>67</ID>
      <DefaultText>If Rem read Another Man's Mirror

(Slightly different description. Extra choice.)</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>68</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you make up your mind to do nothing, the walls around you blur into a red haze, and something that feels like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>69</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell him about your encounter with Aurigan on the balcony.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>70</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him what to do with a bully</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>71</ID>
      <DefaultText>Excuse yourself.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>72</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him if he would be willing to talk to Veresterios about Aurigan. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>73</ID>
      <DefaultText>He nods, but doesn't look up. "I sympathize, girl. The boy is a spoiled brat with the manners of a laak. But he is the master's son, so we must bear it until he leaves us again, may the makers grant it be soon."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>74</ID>
      <DefaultText>He chuckles. "Why do you think I work in a library? It was my solution to that very question. I removed myself from their company and lost myself in books. I would advise you to do the same."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>75</ID>
      <DefaultText>He shakes his head. "So you broke my train of thought for nothing? Idiot girl."

He returns to his work.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>76</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him to help you find a way to deal with Aurigan. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>77</ID>
      <DefaultText>Thank him.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>78</ID>
      <DefaultText>He laughs. "That would be surest way to unemployment I could imagine. Verseterios is as kind a master as one could wish for, but he dotes on that boy and won't hear a word against him. The only thing that *might* turn him against him would be if Aurigan was fool enough to steal from the library."

He turns to you and his eyes soften. "Listen, girl. I know you've a stack of books hidden in the closet. If you find that the pain of the world cannot be borne, go read them and escape. That's what they're for."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>79</ID>
      <DefaultText>He looks up at you, eyes wide with fear. "What are you saying, girl. Deal with him? In what way?"

He waves hands, frantic. "No no no, don't tell me! I don't want to hear. And if I do hear, I'm telling Veresterios, you understand me? You can't go around threatening the master's son! Now, leave me alone. I have no time for nonsense."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>80</ID>
      <DefaultText>He turns back to his book. "Mmm, yes. Back to work."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>81</ID>
      <DefaultText>It won't be easy. You'll have to trick Aurigan into stealing the Diary of Eosus, and then prove to Veresterios that his son was the thief. 

To do this, you'll need to put the Mindeye on the singing moth so it will record the theft. Then you'll need to convince Gurek to suggest to Aurigan that the book could cover his gambling debts and make him a fortune as well. But if Aurigan is kicked out, Gurek loses his job, so the easiest way to get the Bayan's cooperation is to find him a new employer. 

Finally, once you've got the evidence you need, you'll have to tell Veresterios about the theft. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>82</ID>
      <DefaultText>Killing Aurigan shouldn't be too difficult, but killing him without implicating yourself or any of the other Nil is going to be tricky. 

Tricking Veresterios into thinking Aurigan commited suicide by jumping off the balcony seems like a viable plan, but pulling it off will require several steps. First, you'll need to convince the other Nil to help you, because he's too big to push over yourself. Second, you'll need to forge a suicide note. Third, you have to get Gurek away from Aurigan's door so you can sneak in and leave the note, then get him to chase you to the balcony where the other Nil will be waiting. 

Then all you'll have to do is push. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>83</ID>
      <DefaultText>Making Aurigan a better person is the noblest plan, but it won't be easy, and it could lead to driving him mad if the proper steps aren't taken - even if they are. 

First, you'll need to steal the Mindeye and wear it for a week, recording all your waking and sleeping moments. Then you'll have to get Gurek away from Aurigan's room so you can sneak in and place the Mindeye behind Aurigan's ear, forcing him to experience a week's worth of being a Nil in a single night. And if you want to keep him from going mad, you'll have to dose him with alcohol once every hour and hope it's enough. 

Otherwise he might end up a gibbering lunatic and you wouldn't want that - or would you?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>84</ID>
      <DefaultText>Talk to Coi about Aurigan. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>85</ID>
      <DefaultText>Talk to Gurek about Aurigan.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>86</ID>
      <DefaultText>You slip out and find Coi and his crew polishing the floor of a wide hallway. He gives you a hopeful look. 

"Have you thought of something?" he asks.

He is disappointed when you say you have not, but is willing to answer your questions.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>87</ID>
      <DefaultText>You find Gurek napping on a bench outside Aurigan's apartments, massive arms folded across his barrel chest. He opens one eye as you approach.

"What d'you want?" he asks. His voice sounds like stone wheels crushing bones.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>88</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him if he thinks getting Veresterios to kick Aurigan out is the best idea.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>89</ID>
      <DefaultText>Asks him if he thinks they could get away with killing Aurigan.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>90</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him if he thinks it would be possible to make Aurigan a nicer person.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>91</ID>
      <DefaultText>Thank him and leave.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>92</ID>
      <DefaultText>He beams. "That would be wonderful, but I don't know what would do the trick. The old man is as blind as a cave crab when it comes to his son's faults."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>93</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi looks around to see if anybody heard, then whispers. "He certainly deserves it, but there would be one hell of a shist storm afterward, wouldn't there? We'd all get the chop for certain. No Nil in the house would survive."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>94</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi laughs, then claps his hand over his mouth and looks around the silent corridor. 

"II think you'd have an easier time of it trying to pull a juriskar through a drainpipe by the tail," he whispers. "That boy is mean all the way down to the bone. As cold as a fish cutter's knife."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>95</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi nods and waves. "Thanks, Rem. We're counting on you."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>96</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him if he'll help if you can make sure the Nil won't be blamed. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>97</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell him you'll take care of it and make sure the Nil won't be blamed.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>98</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell him you need to think about it. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>99</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi swallows. "I don't know, Rem. That's... that's a big step. You'd have to guarantee it, and even then."

He shakes his head. "I don't know."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>100</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi gives you a long look. "I know I asked for your help, Rem, but don't go dying for our sake. Please."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>101</ID>
      <DefaultText>He nods. "I would. That's a big step. You could bring the whole world down on us if it went wrong."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>102</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him if he would really have dropped the two Nil off the balcony.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>103</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him why he would agree to kill a fellow servant.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>104</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell him you were just passing by. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>105</ID>
      <DefaultText>He ponders this for a long time, then grunts. "I need my job, just like you need yours. Though..." He shifts, uncomfortable. "Though you might like yours better."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>106</ID>
      <DefaultText>He ponders this for a long time, then grunts. "Why don't you talk back to that snotty librarian?" He shifts, uncomfortable. "I know. It's not the same, but I need this job, no matter what I think of it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>107</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Then keep walking," he says.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>108</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him if he'd help get Aurigan kicked out of the house.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>109</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him if he'd help kill Aurigan.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>110</ID>
      <DefaultText>Say farewell. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>111</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek raises one heavy brow. "You got a scheme? Hmmm. Maybe. If you found me a better job first. Otherwise, you and me'll tangle. And I'm guessing you'll get the worst of it."

{SCRIPT: Sets Knows Gurek is Looking For Work conditional.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>112</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek turns and looks at you straight on. "Don't have much love for the boss, but he doesn't die on my watch, understand." He cracks his knuckles. "I hear you're planning something, I go to Veresterios. You make your move, I kill you. Understand?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>113</ID>
      <DefaultText>He gives you a nod. "So long."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>114</ID>
      <DefaultText>Find Gurek a new employer</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>115</ID>
      <DefaultText>Steal the Mindeye.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: Does not appear if this step was completed in another plan.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>116</ID>
      <DefaultText>Convince Gurek to tell Aurigan about the Diary of Eosus.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: This version plays if you did not get Gurek a job.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>117</ID>
      <DefaultText>Place the Mindeye on the singing moth. 

[NEEDS A FOLLOW UP]

{SCRIPT: Does not play if Rem doesn't have the Mindeye.}
{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT:Can be tried multiple times. Easier after the first time.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>119</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him what Aurigan's like. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>120</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek snorts. "Bored, drunk and deep in debt. All he's done since we've been back is go to the game house and lose at tiles. That's why he's always so angry. He's desperate."

He sighs. "I'll die protecting him from the shin men one night, I guarantee it."

{SCRIPT: Sets Know Aurigan is in Debt conditional.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>121</ID>
      <DefaultText>Here are all the options. 

{Only plays if you've unlocked all options.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>122</ID>
      <DefaultText>Use a stirring speech from "Jaws of Victory" to convince other Nil to help kill Aurigan.

{SCRIPT: Free pass if the PC has read Jaws of Victory.}
{SCRIPT: Does not play if global, Nil Won't Help Kill Aurigan has been set.}
{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>123</ID>
      <DefaultText>Forge Aurigan's suicide note.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>124</ID>
      <DefaultText>Sneak into Aurigan's room.

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC Got Gurek Away From Door.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>125</ID>
      <DefaultText>Try to trick Gurek into leaving Aurigan's door by telling him there is someone disreputable at the front door asking for Aurigan.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: Sets global, Tried to Trick Gurek into Leaving.}
{SCRIPT: Does not play if you've tried to trick Gurek into leaving before.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>126</ID>
      <DefaultText>Steal the Mindeye.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: Does not appear if this step was completed in another plan.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>127</ID>
      <DefaultText>Acquire alcohol to mitigate the madness-inducing effects of the Mindeye.

{SCRIPT: Doesn't play if 245 has played: Acquire stimulants to increase the madness-inducing effects of the Mindeye. }</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>128</ID>
      <DefaultText>Trick Gurek into leaving Aurigan's door by telling him there is someone disreputable at the front door asking for Aurigan.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: Sets global, Tried to Trick Gurek into Leaving.}
{SCRIPT: Does not play if you've tried to trick Gurek into leaving before.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>129</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take the final step to make Aurigan a better person. Put Mindeye on Aurigan.

{SCRIPT: Only playa if PC is In Aurigan's Room.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>130</ID>
      <DefaultText>Speaking with Coi, you think you can use the servant's grapevine to find Gurek a more suitable employer, but it may take time, and who knows what terror Aurigan might inflict upon the servants while you wait for an answer. On the other hand, Gurek will be much more helpful if you can assure him he will have a job after Aurigan is thrown out. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>131</ID>
      <DefaultText>Veresterios was very careful to lock the Mindeye in Lanalton's desk, but Lanalton is not very careful with the spare key. When he goes to the lavatory you easily unlock the desk drawer, take the Mindeye out, and relock the drawer, then place the spare key back where you found it. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Rem has the Mindeye}
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>132</ID>
      <DefaultText>You turn your focus to a different task.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>133</ID>
      <DefaultText>Work on another plan.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>134</ID>
      <DefaultText>Wait until Aurigan has stolen the Diary of Eosus, then take the final step by telling Veresterios and Lanalton that the book is missing and you might be able to expose the thief.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>135</ID>
      <DefaultText>You're not ready. The plan won't succeed unless all the pieces are in place. Have another look at it, or maybe try another plan. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>136</ID>
      <DefaultText>The two Sona stare at you, stunned, then Lanalton barks at you. "You lying runt! I don't believe you! It must be here!"

"Aye," says Veresterios. "Find it!"

Though you know it's pointless, you help them search the shelves and table tops. You find nothing. 

Veresterios turns on you. "You said you know who did this? Who was it?"

You tell him that, having recently suspected intruders in the library, you put the Mindeye on the singing moth in the hope it might see who was skuling around. 

"How dare you use such a valuable device without permission!" shouts Lanalton. "You shall be whipped!"

"Never mind about that," says Veresterios. "Bring me the device. I must see!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>137</ID>
      <DefaultText>Waiting until both Veresterios and Lanalton have retired for the evening, you open the moth's cage and reach in with a towel. It batters you with frightened wings, but you manage to wrap it in the towel and part the fur at the back of its head and press the Mindeye against it's exposed carapace. The device adheres in a way you don't understand, for it secretes no glue or hooks, but it stays where it is placed, and the fur hides it from sight. 

You release the moth into the cage again and it flutters around, agitated, singing an angry song while you creep away, hands sprinkled with moth dust. 

[NEEDS A FOLLOW UP]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>138</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek stares at you, eyes dull. "I'm gonna lose my job over this. But maybe it's time. I'm sick of breaking arms." He nods. "Okay. I'll tell him about the book. He'll jump at the chance to pay off the shin men. Be ready."

{SCRIPT: Sets a global "Gurek tells Aurigan about Book"}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>139</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take final step in your plan to murder Aurigan by tricking him into chasing you to the balcony.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>140</ID>
      <DefaultText>Use the Mindeye to record a week of being a Nil.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: This does not play if PC has not stolen Mindeye.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>141</ID>
      <DefaultText>Most of the Nil in the servants hall nod as you finish your speech, moved, but some are still not on board. There is much murmuring.

"Murder?" says Jaya, the housekeeper. "We'll all be killed."

"Not with Rem's plan," says Coi. "You heard her. She's going to forge a suicide note. It'll look like Aurigan killed himself." He raises his voice over the heated debate. "We've been lucky so far. Only a few beatings and broken bones, but you know it won't last. Him or his Bayan will kill one of us eventually. Are you willing to just let it happen?"

After much discussion, you and Coi manage to convince a group of ten to help you, and the others grudingly go along.

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Nil Agree to Help Kill Aurigan.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>142</ID>
      <DefaultText>The hardest part of the forgery is finding samples of Aurigan's writing to learn from. He doesn't write much. Finally, however, you discover a notebook from his travels that he left in the library, and you begin. 

Two days later, after staying up late each night, practicing with stolen pen and paper, you feel you have the idiosyncracies of his style down pat and you write and sign a simple note. "Forgive me, Father. I cannot face my debts or the shame I have brought to my family. This is the end." 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Suicide Note Written.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>143</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek grunts, then uncrosses his arms and stands. "I told that thumb-breaker never to come here. Excuse me."

He walks in the direction of the stairs.

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Got Gurek Away From Door.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>144</ID>
      <DefaultText>With Gurek out of the way, entering Aurigan's room is as simple as opening the door.

It is a large, luxurious room, with a lessened-gravity bed hovering in one corner and beautiful works of art on the walls. There are also underclothes and dirty cups and plates scattered across the floor. The place is a mess.

Aurigan snores in the bed, dead to the world. 

{SCRIPT: Sets Global, In Aurigan's Room.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>146</ID>
      <DefaultText>You're not ready. The plan won't succeed unless all the pieces are in place. Have another look at it, or maybe try another plan. 

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC has not placed the suicide note or hasn't recruited the other Nil}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>147</ID>
      <DefaultText>He leaps unsteadily at you, and you dart for the door. He stumbles after, snarling. "Come back here! Do you think this is a game? Gurek! Gurek, where are you?"

You run out the door and he follows, trying to catch his breath enough to shout, and you soon lead him to the balcony, where he stops, weaving and wheezing, and stares at the assembled Nil. 

"What is this?" he asks. "A party? Are you all star gazing?"

The Nil stare back at him, hesitating. You can see the fear in their eyes now that they're faced with the reality of the plan. It looks like they might run. 

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>148</ID>
      <DefaultText>You're not ready. The plan won't succeed unless all the pieces are in place. Have another look at it, or maybe try another plan. 

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC does not have the Mindeye, or has not Worn the Mindeye, or both.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>149</ID>
      <DefaultText>You pull back Aurigan's long white hair and press the Mindeye to his skull, just behind his ear. The device adheres in a way you don't understand, for it secretes no glue or hooks, but it stays where it is placed. 

You turn it to the 'view' setting and speed it up.  Immediately he tenses and you can see his eyes moving behind his eyelids. His limbs start twitching too, and he begins murmuring under his breath.
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>150</ID>
      <DefaultText>Veresterios was very careful to lock the Mindeye in Lanalton's desk, but Lanalton is not very careful with the spare key. When he goes to the lavatory you easily unlock the desk drawer, take the Mindeye out, and relock the drawer, then place the spare key back where you found it. 

{SCRIPT: Rem has the Mindeye}
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>151</ID>
      <DefaultText>You search the kitchen and find plenty of alcohol, and also a carafe of strong tea. It would be easy to steal either. Or both. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>152</ID>
      <DefaultText>For a week you wear the Mindeye behind your ear, recording every moment of your life - the drudgery, the abuses, both minor and major, from your Sona masters and their Bayan enforcers. The slights, the insults, the shoves, the casual threats, the stories of the other Nil, the fear of losing your job, the fear of dying to keep it, your dreams of freedom, your rage, your sorrow, your infrequent joys, your courage, your cowardice, your pettiness, your simple humanity. 

Several times during the week, Aurigan accosts you, leering, joking, insulting you, making unwanted advances, threatening you with violence. You wonder how he will react to being abused by himself.

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Wore the Mindeye.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>153</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek grunts, then uncrosses his arms and stands. "I told that thumb-breaker never to come here. Excuse me."

He walks in the direction of the stairs.

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Got Gurek Away From Door.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>154</ID>
      <DefaultText>Sneak into Aurigan's room.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC Got Gurek Away From Door.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>155</ID>
      <DefaultText>With Gurek out of the way, entering Aurigan's room is as simple as opening the door.

It is a large, luxurious room, with a lessened-gravity bed hovering in one corner and beautiful works of art on the walls. There are also underclothes and dirty cups and plates scattered across the floor. The place is a mess.

Aurigan snores in the bed, face down and dead to the world. It would be the work of a moment to to place the Mindeye behind his ear. 

{SCRIPT: Sets Global, In Aurigan's Room.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>156</ID>
      <DefaultText>Are you sure you want to do it that way?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>157</ID>
      <DefaultText>Are you sure you want to do this without enlisting the help of the other Nil? You may not be strong enough to push Aurigan off the balcony yourself.

{SCRIPT: Only appears if PC has not recruited other Nil.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>158</ID>
      <DefaultText>Are you sure you want to this without having any alcohol on hand to help him mitigate the effects of the Mindeye? Without it, the posibility that he could go mad is quite high. 

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC does not have Alcohol or Tea.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>159</ID>
      <DefaultText>Give evidence of Moth</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>160</ID>
      <DefaultText>"What!" says Aurigan. "Who says I have stolen from you? They are a liar!"

Veresterios holds out the Mindeye. "Put it to your eye and twist it one click to the right. You will see he who has condemned you."

Aurigan snatches the device from his father's hand, then watches it. A moment later his jaw drops, and he flings it from him. "How...? How...?"

Veresterios indicates you. "Rem put it on the moth. It saw all."

Aurigan turns on you, shaking. "You. You did this for vengeance, didn't you? Because I threatened your grubby little friends. Well, I'll kill you for it. It's the Bore for you, you little tattle tale!"

He charges you, eyes crazed, hands extended.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>161</ID>
      <DefaultText>Accept blame. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>162</ID>
      <DefaultText>END MERE</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>163</ID>
      <DefaultText>Blame Lanalton</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>164</ID>
      <DefaultText>END MERE</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>165</ID>
      <DefaultText>Yes.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>166</ID>
      <DefaultText>No.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>167</ID>
      <DefaultText>""</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>169</ID>
      <DefaultText>Yes.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>170</ID>
      <DefaultText>No.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>171</ID>
      <DefaultText>""</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>172</ID>
      <DefaultText>""</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>173</ID>
      <DefaultText>Rally Nil to push him, and start pushing Aurigan yourself. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>174</ID>
      <DefaultText>Rally Nil to push Aurigan, but don't help. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>175</ID>
      <DefaultText>Keep quiet and try to push Aurigan over yourself. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>176</ID>
      <DefaultText>At your urging, the Nil join you, quickly and silently surrounding Aurigan and shoving him toward the edge.

"What are you doing?" he squawks. "Let go of me this instant!"

As the Nil's momentum forces Aurigan closer to the balustrade, he grabs you and tries to use you as a weapon against the others. It doesn't work, and he starts tipping backwards over the balustrade - and taking you with him. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>177</ID>
      <DefaultText>At your urging, the Nil quickly and silently surround Aurigan and shove him toward the edge.

"What are you doing?" he squawks. "Let go of me this instant!"

As the Nil's momentum forces Aurigan closer to the balustrade, he grabs Coi and tries to use him as a weapon against the others. It doesn't work, and he starts tipping backwards over the balustrade - and taking Coi with him. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>178</ID>
      <DefaultText>Your solitary attack on Aurigan inspires the others to come forward, and they start helping you shove him toward the edge.

Unfortunately, he's got a good grip on you, and uses you as weapon to knock the others back. Your struggling, however, throws him off balance, and he falls against the balustrade. A pair of Nil see this as an opening and rush in to slam into his shoulder. 

Aurigan looses his footing and topples over the edge... taking you with him. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>179</ID>
      <DefaultText>Put the Mindeye on Aurigan without getting some alcohol first. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>180</ID>
      <DefaultText>Wait look around for some alcohol before putting the Mindeye on Aurigan. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>181</ID>
      <DefaultText>You pull back Aurigan's long white hair and press the Mindeye to his skull, just behind his ear. The device adheres in a way you don't understand, for it secretes no glue or hooks, but it stays where it is placed. 

You turn it to the 'view' setting and speed it up.  Immediately he tenses and you can see his eyes moving behind his eyelids. His limbs start twitching too, and he begins murmuring under his breath.

A little while later, you hear Gurek return to his post outside the door, and you hide. He looks in on Aurigan, then backs out again when he sees him asleep. After that there are no intrusions for the rest of the night. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>182</ID>
      <DefaultText>You search the room and find both a bottle of wine and some haffa juice. You could use either on him if you wanted.

As you approach him again, you see he is still fast asleep. 

{SCRIPT: Sets Has Alcohol Global.}
{SCRIPT: Sets Has Haffa Juice Global.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>183</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stay with him and give him hourly doses of wine until it's time to take the Mindeye off again.

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC Has Alcohol.}
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>184</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stay with him and do nothing until it's time to take the Mindeye off again.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>185</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stay with him and dose him with strong tea until it's time to take the Mindeye off again.

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC Has Tea.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>186</ID>
      <DefaultText>Though you fear he might wake, you ease Aurigan over on his back and pull gently on his chin, opening his mouth. Thankfully, this does not jar him out of his immersive dream, and you are able to dribble a bit of wine into his mouth. He swallows it reflexively, then, after a minute his twitching lessens, and he seems to relax. 

A little while later, you hear Gurek return to his post outside the door, and you hide. He looks in on Aurigan, then backs out again when he sees him asleep. After that there are no intrusions for the rest of the night, and you are free to give him his wine every hour. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>187</ID>
      <DefaultText>Aurigan continues to twitch and mutter anxiously without ceasing, but he does not wake. 

A little while later, you hear Gurek return to his post outside the door, and you hide. He looks in on Aurigan, then backs out again when he sees him asleep. After that there are no intrusions for the rest of the night. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>188</ID>
      <DefaultText>Though you fear he might wake, you ease Aurigan over on his back and pull gently on his chin, opening his mouth. Thankfully, this does not jar him out of his immersive dream, and you are able to dribble a bit of tea into his mouth. He swallows it reflexively, and after a minute his twitching and moaning increases. He begins to whimper. 

A little while later, you hear Gurek return to his post outside the door, and you hide. He looks in on Aurigan, pauses as he sees him so restless, then shrugs and backs out again. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>189</ID>
      <DefaultText>Flee.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>190</ID>
      <DefaultText>Fight. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>191</ID>
      <DefaultText>Surrender. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>192</ID>
      <DefaultText>You turn and run, but Aurigan catches you in a step and throws you over his shoulder, then strides for the balcony. There is nothing you can do. He is far stronger than you. Your struggles are futile.

Then, out of the corner of your eye, you see Veresterios raise a device like a pen. A green light blinds you and you are on the ground, twitching beside Aurigan, who is doing the same. 

Veresterios stands over his son. "I see now you are everything the Nil said you were. Gurek, remove this trash from my house, and help the girl to her feet. Though she tried to flee, she will still be rewarded for bringing this villainy to my attention."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>193</ID>
      <DefaultText>You swing for Aurigan's jaw, but he swats your fist aside and throws you over his shoulder, then strides for the balcony. There is nothing you can do. He is far stronger than you. Your struggles are futile.

Then, out of the corner of your eye, you see Veresterios raise a device like a pen. A green light blinds you and you are on the ground, twitching beside Aurigan, who is doing the same. 

Veresterios stands over his son. "I see now you are everything the Nil said you were. Gurek, remove this trash from my house, and take the girl too. She was brave to bring this villainy to my attention, but she swung at Aurigan just now, and striking a Sona is forbidden. She'll have to go."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>194</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you sink to your knees in submission, Aurigan catches you and throws you over his shoulder, then strides for the balcony. There is nothing you can do. He is far stronger than you. Your struggles are futile.

Then, out of the corner of your eye, you see Veresterios raise a device like a pen. A green light blinds you and you are on the ground, twitching beside Aurigan, who is doing the same. 

Veresterios stands over his son. "I see now you are everything the Nil said you were. Gurek, remove this trash from my house, and help the girl to her feet. She will be rewarded for bringing this villainy to my attention."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>195</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The Mindeye it's called," says the older man, holding up the object. It looks like a jade button. "A fascinating toy. Place it behind your ear and set it to "See" and it will capture all that you experience - sight, touch, taste, thought, emotion. Place it behind someone else's ear and set it to "Show," and they will experience everything you captured. A completely immersive experience."

"Remarkable, Lord Veresterios," says the younger man. "Could you put it on an animal, do you suppose?"

"Certainly you could," said the older man. "A pet, a beast, an insect, even an emptyheaded Nil like our dear little Rem here."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>196</ID>
      <DefaultText>Run out and attack Gurek</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>197</ID>
      <DefaultText>The massive servant hardly even notices your punches, but Aurigan does, and grabs you from behind, laughing. 

"Look, Gurek. A cave flea, trying to bite your leg."  He spins around so you both face the Nil with the mop. "Now you have three to pick from, drit. Make your choice. Now!"

The Nil looks from you to the two Nil in Gurek's arms. Tears are streaming down his face. "Please, master. I... take me. Let them go and--"

"That wasn't a choice, fool!" snarls Aurigan. "Now--"

But before he can repeat himself, Veresterios' voice comes from inside. 

"Aurigan, my boy! Where are you! We're waiting for you!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>198</ID>
      <DefaultText>The young sona cringes, then shoves you away and beckons to Gurek. "Kill the left hand one. The old man calls."

Gurek obediently drops the Nil in his left hand into the abyss, then follows his master as the other Nil weep. 

"You see, Rem?" says the one with the mop. "He's a monster. He had poor Dal killed for *nothing*. I..." He breaks down again.

"Coi's right," says the other Nil. "Him and that Bayan will kill us all. There's already three maids out with broken arms. And old Jai died of a cracked head last night."

Coi clutches your arm. "You promised you would help us, Rem, so please! You've got more freedom and smarts than any Nil we know. Find some way to... to make him stop."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>199</ID>
      <DefaultText>The young sona cringes, then shoves you away and beckons to Gurek. "Kill the left hand one. The old man calls."

Gurek obediently drops the Nil in his left hand into the abyss, then follows his master as the other Nil weep. 

