Coi clutches your arm. "You promised you would help us, Rem, so please! You've got more freedom and smarts than any Nil we know. Find some way to... to make him stop."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>201</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek obediently drops the Nil in his left hand into the abyss, then turns and follows his master  past you into the library. As the Nil watch them go, weeping, they see you. 

"You see, Rem?" says the one with the mop. "He's a monster. He had poor Dal killed for *nothing*. I..." He breaks down again.

"Coi's right," says the second Nil. "Him and that Bayan of his will kill us all. There's already three maids out with broken arms. And old Jai died of a cracked head last night."

Coi clutches your arm. "You promised you would help us, Rem, so please! You've got more freedom and smarts than any Nil we know. Find some way to... to make him stop."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>202</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stop exploring the library. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>203</ID>
      <DefaultText>Lanalton is still buried in his books. You are momentarily free to do as you wish. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>204</ID>
      <DefaultText>Fynn laughed and tossed a pair of glittering gems on table. "Do you recognize these, madam?"

Lady Sommari stared. "Those are my dream jewels! Lost since last Chela's Day! Did you steal them, you bold rascal? I shall send for the levies!"

"Not I, madam," said Fynn. "But send for the levies nonetheless, for the thief is among us. Here is the proof." He threw down a pawn broker's note and pointed at the signature. "Do you know that scrawl?"

Lady Sommari gasped and turned to her son. "Ambruck! How could you! You are disinherited this instant!"

Beside him, Fora embraced Ran. "Oh, darling, I knew you would be lord of Sommari one day! And it's all thanks to the Laughing Jack!"

{SCRIPT: Is it possible to set the text of the book in italic, or differentiate it from the normal discriptive text of the Mere?}
{SCRIPT: Sets read the Laughing Jack conditional.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>205</ID>
      <DefaultText>By the time we'd reached the Enstal line we'd had enough. The whole squad was in agreement, Hyrnhol had to go. He'd already got half of us killed in the Dool thanks to his cowardice and shilly-shallying, and his decision at Bresadt proved he hadn't gained any wisdom since. The only question was how to do it. Outright murder would get us all the chop, and the higher-ups were wise to the usual friendly-fire and "accidental" ordinance malfunction ploys. We had to be subtle.  

Then Gerrisae hit on it. We'd all heard Hyrnhal moaning about his wife leaving him, and so had the brass. If we wrote a note in his hand saying her betrayal had driven him to the brink, well, who'd gainsay it?

{SCRIPT: Is it possible to set the text of the book in italic, or differentiate it from the normal discriptive text of the Mere?}
{SCRIPT: Sets read the Jaws of Victory conditional.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>206</ID>
      <DefaultText>The secret to peace is empathy. If we could all live for a time in our enemies' heads, and if they could live in ours, then conflict would be impossible, for they would understand our pain and we would understand theirs. Our life experiences would be shared. We would be family. Closer than family. We would be one. And who but a madman could make war upon himself?

{SCRIPT: Is it possible to set the text of the book in italic, or differentiate it from the normal discriptive text of the Mere?}
{SCRIPT: Sets read Another Man's Mirror conditional.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>207</ID>
      <DefaultText>Do not attempt to view another's experiences while under the influence of stimulants, particularly at elevated viewing speeds. Tea, wakeleaf, haffa juice, all make it harder for the mind to accept the experiences of another mind as one's own, and this can lead to madness and death. Indeed, the best way to insure the sanity of the user is to administer small doses of intoxicants hourly until the viewing is complete.

{SCRIPT: Is it possible to set the text of the book in italic, or differentiate it from the normal discriptive text of the Mere?}
{SCRIPT: Sets read about the Mind Eye conditional.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>208</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him if he knows anything you can use against Aurigan. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>209</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi shakes his head. "I wish I did, but he's been away in the Steadfast since he was twelve. I know nothing about who he is now." He laughs. "I'm sure Gurek could tell you, if you dared ask."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>210</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him why he doesn't like his job.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>211</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek shrugs. "It was fine before. The boss traveled, so I traveled. Saw the world. Kept him safe. Now we're back, he wants me to pick on grubs like you. No honor in that."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>212</ID>
      <DefaultText>You don't know enough to come up with a coherent plan yet. Perhaps it would help to go back and talk to more people, or explore the library some more.

{SCRIPT: Plays if PC hasn't done any of the following: examined the moth, read about the mindeye, learned about Aurigan's debts from Gurek.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>213</ID>
      <DefaultText>You don't know enough to come up with a coherent plan yet. Perhaps it would help to go back and talk to more people, or explore the library some more.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>214</ID>
      <DefaultText>You don't know enough to come up with a coherent plan yet. Perhaps it would help to go back and talk to more people, or explore the library some more.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>215</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek shakes his massive head. "I know you're trying to save your people, but I gotta live too. You get the boss thrown out, I'm out of a job. Sorry. Find me a place to land, maybe we can talk."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>216</ID>
      <DefaultText>""</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>217</ID>
      <DefaultText>""</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>218</ID>
      <DefaultText>""</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>219</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take your time and try to find Gurek the best employer you can.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>220</ID>
      <DefaultText>Call in every favor and try to find Gurek a new employer within two days. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>221</ID>
      <DefaultText>Forget about finding Gurek a new employer. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>222</ID>
      <DefaultText>You have strained Mer's friendships to the limit, and put her in debt with bribes she could not afford, but you managed to find a better job for Gurek - guardian at a grain warehouse. It's not an interesting job, but it also doesn't involve hurting innocent people. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Rem has found Gurek a Job.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>223</ID>
      <DefaultText>You strained Mer's friendships to the limit, and put her in debt with bribes she could not afford, but still could not conjure up a job for Gurek. Maybe a longer search might yield results. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>224</ID>
      <DefaultText>After a week of searching, wheedling, and outright bribery, you find the perfect job for Gurek. A feeble old Sona needs a patient and able-bodied Bayan to help him move from room to room in his overlarge house. Gurek won't have to hurt anyone against his will ever again.

Unfortunately, while you searched, Aurigan broke Coi's collar bone by shoving him down the stairs, and blackened the eyes of a maid. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Rem has found Gurek a Job.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>225</ID>
      <DefaultText>You turn your focus to other tasks. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>227</ID>
      <DefaultText>Try again to find Gurek a new employer. 

{SCRIPT: Only appears once 114 plays once.)</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>228</ID>
      <DefaultText>Right. Where were you?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>229</ID>
      <DefaultText>Where did you leave off?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>230</ID>
      <DefaultText>Hmmm. Where did you leave off?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>231</ID>
      <DefaultText>Waiting until both Veresterios and Lanalton have retired for the evening, you open the moth's cage and reach in with a towel. It batters you with frightened wings and bites you though the towel. You hiss and fall back, upsetting a stack of books.

There is movement in the hallway. Someone has heard you. You quickly close the cage door again, right the books, then creep away as the moth flutters around, agitated, singing an angry song. 

[NEEDS A FOLLOW UP]</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>232</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell Gurek you found him a job, and get him to tell Aurigan about the Diary of Eosus.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: This version only plays if you got Gurek a job.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>233</ID>
      <DefaultText>A spark of hope glimmers in the big man's eyes. "You found me job? Good. Then I'll do it. I'll tell Aurigan about the book. He'll jump at the chance to pay off the shin men. Be ready."

{SCRIPT: Sets a global "Gurek tells Aurigan about Book"}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>234</ID>
      <DefaultText>With careful hands, Lanalton takes the Mindeye off the moth and hands it to Veresterios. The old sona puts it to his eye and twists it to speed up the viewing. For a long time, he just watches, then he stops it, twists it back and watches a short section again. His face sags and he lowers the Mindeye to his lap. 

"Lanalton," he says. "Send for my son."

A few moments later, Aurigan slouches into the library, looking put out, with Gurek behind him. "What is it?" he asks. "I was busy."

Veresterios shakes his head. "I have forgiven you much, Aurigan. Blamed much on your youth. But that you would steal from your own father. That is too much. You are no longer my son."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>235</ID>
      <DefaultText>As Gurek lowers his giant hand to your small one and helps you stand, he and Veresterios and Lanalton all blur into a red haze around you, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>236</ID>
      <DefaultText>As Gurek hauls you to your feet, he and Veresterios and Lanalton all blur into a red haze around you, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>237</ID>
      <DefaultText>As Gurek lowers his giant hand to your small one and helps you stand, he and Veresterios and Lanalton all blur into a red haze around you, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>238</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek shrugs. "Tell the Bayan downstairs to deal with him. He's not worth my time, and I'm sure not waking the boss about it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>239</ID>
      <DefaultText>You step to the bed and slap Aurigan across the face. It takes several slaps to wake him up, but finally he sits up and looks around with bleary eyes. 

"Who?" he asks.

Then he sees you, and his eyes narrow. "Did you just--"

You slap him again and he roars up out of the covers, dressed only in his undergarments. "Impertinant slut! I'll kill you for this!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>240</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi doesn't allow it. As Aurigan topples over the edge, Coi pulls you from his arms and sets you on the balcony floor, hugging you while the Sona's screams echo up from the Core. 

"You did it!" says Coi. "You saved us. We can't thank you enough."

But as the Nil begin to disperse, a coldness comes over you. You have ended a man's life tonight. Was it the best way, or just the easiest?

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>241</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you start back to your room, the walls around you blur into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the moonlight, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness, but the questions in your heart still remain. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>242</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Nil try to pull Coi from Aurigan's arms but the Sona topples over the edge before they can get him free. Aurigan and Coi fall into the Core together, screaming as they drop. 

The assempled Nil stare after them for a long time, then slowly and quietly begin to disperse. None of them look at you. 

You too look into the abyss. You freed the Nil from Aurigan's tyranny, but at the cost of Coi's life. Was it worth the trade? Should you have done more to help? Should you have found another way?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>243</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi screams and reaches for you, nearly throwing himself over the rail to try to grab you, but he's too late, and you see his horrified face receding above you as you fall, the walls of the Bore closing in and Aurigan shrieking in your ear. 

You freed the Nil from his tyranny at the cost of your own life - and his. Was it the best way? Or was there another way where no one had to die?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>244</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you plummet deeper and deeper into the Bore, the gantries and catwalks you fall past begin to blur into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. Aurigan, the Bore, all of Haref vanishes into silent darkness, but the questions in your heart still remain. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>245</ID>
      <DefaultText>Acquire stimulants to increase the madness-inducing effects of the Mindeye. 

{SCRIPT: Doesn't play if 127 has played: Acquire alcohol to mitigate the madness-inducing effects of the Mindeye.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>246</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take the alcohol. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>247</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take the tea.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>248</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take both.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>249</ID>
      <DefaultText>You slip a small bottle of wine into your servant's tunic. No one notices. 

{SCRIPT: Sets Has Alcohol Global.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>250</ID>
      <DefaultText>You slip the carafe of tea into your servant's tunic. No one notices. 

{SCRIPT: Sets Has Tea Global.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>251</ID>
      <DefaultText>You slip a small bottle of wine and the carafe of tea into your servant's tunic. You slosh a bit when you walk, but no one notices. 

{SCRIPT: Sets Has Alcohol Global.}
{SCRIPT: Sets Has Tea Global.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>252</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek shrugs. "Tell the Bayan downstairs to deal with him. He's not worth my time, and I'm sure not waking the boss about it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>253</ID>
      <DefaultText>END MERE</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>254</ID>
      <DefaultText>Just as dawn begins to color the sky outside Aurigan's windows, the Mindeye chirps to indicate that it has show him all of your experiences. 

You peel it from behind his ear and sneak for the door, hoping that it worked, and that Gurek is asleep outside. A voice behind you turns you around. It's Aurigan.

"Wait," he says, sitting up in bed. "I... I know what you did and why you did it. It was all in what you showed me. I should be mad at your violation of my sovereign self and my free will, but... but you also showed that that is what I do to you - and your kin - every day."

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>255</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I promise you," he says. "That will change. I have spent too long thinking only *I* had a mind, only I knew pain. My father's Nil need never fear me again. However..." He raises his eyes to yours. "I do not want you in his house any longer. It would be too strange. But know that you succeeded in changing me. Now go. I will ask my father to find you a good place."

As you bow to him, the walls of his room blur into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. Aurigan and the pink sky beyond his windows all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>256</ID>
      <DefaultText>Just as dawn begins to color the sky outside Aurigan's windows, the Mindeye chirps to indicate that it has show him all of your experiences. 

You peel it from behind his ear and sneak for the door, hoping that it worked, and that Gurek is asleep outside. A voice behind you turns you around. It's Aurigan.

"You little bitch," he says, sitting up in bed and glaring groggily at you. "That's right. I know what you did, and why you did it. It was all in what you showed me, what you tried to turn me into." He shudders. "By the makers, it took everything I had to maintain my *self* in that endless nightmare."

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>257</ID>
      <DefaultText>He stands from the bed and steps toward you. "You'll be pleased to know that you achieved your goal. My father's Nil need never fear me again. You showed me that they too have hearts and minds. However..." He raises burning eyes to yours. "The violation you subjected me to was worse than any crime I have ever commited. And you will pay for it - with your life."

As he pounces on you and drags you to the open window, the walls of his room blur into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. Aurigan and the pink sky and the Bore that yawns below you as he throws you out of the room all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>258</ID>
      <DefaultText>After an hour you give Aurigan another few swallows of tea, and once again his agitation grows worse, until he sits up in his bed, screaming, "The Nil are in my head! The Nil are in my head!"

Before you can try to silence him, Gurek slams through the door and looks around. Aurigan points directly at you. "It was her! She put the Nil in my head! I have to get them out! I have to--"

He sceams again and snatches a dagger from his bedside table, then races for the door. Gurek tries to stop him but Aurigan dodges around him, then calls back to him. "This way! To the servant's quarters! We'll start there!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>259</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek heads after his master, then turns back and grabs you by the neck. "You don't deserve it," he rumbles. "But I'll give you the easy way out." And with that, he throws you out the window. 

You sail out into the night air with the stars and moons above you and the yawning black mouth of the Bore below, then begin to fall, speeding past gantries and catwalks and cables. 

As the starlight recedes above you, something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>260</ID>
      <DefaultText>Quote the Laughing Jack and make a witty retort. 

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC read The Laughing Jack.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>261</ID>
      <DefaultText>Aurigan frowns as he catches you and throws you over his shoulder. "Who are you calling a ner-do-well?"

You struggle, but he is much stronger than you, and cutting remarks won't help you as he strides for the balcony. Then, out of the corner of your eye, you see Veresterios raise a device like a pen. A green light blinds you and you are on the ground, twitching beside Aurigan, who is doing the same. 

Veresterios stands over his son. "I see now you are everything the Nil said you were. Gurek, remove this trash from my house, and help the girl to her feet. Despite insulting my son, she will still be rewarded for bringing this villainy to my attention."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>262</ID>
      <DefaultText>As Gurek lowers his giant hand to your small one and helps you stand, he and Veresterios and Lanalton all blur into a red haze around you, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>263</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>264</ID>
      <DefaultText>Place the Mindeye on the singing moth. 

{SCRIPT: Does not play if Rem doesn't have the Mindeye.}
{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT:Can be tried multiple times. Easier after the first time.}
{SCRIPT: Does not play if the Mindeye is already on the Moth.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>265</ID>
      <DefaultText>Try again to place the Mindeye on the singing moth. 

{SCRIPT: Does not play if Rem doesn't have the Mindeye.}
{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT:Can be tried multiple times. Easier after the first time.}
{SCRIPT: Does not play if the Mindeye is already on the Moth.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>266</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>267</ID>
      <DefaultText>Waiting until both Veresterios and Lanalton have retired for the evening, you open the moth's cage and reach in with a towel. It batters you with frightened wings, but you manage to wrap it in the towel and part the fur at the back of its head and press the Mindeye against it's exposed carapace. The device adheres in a way you don't understand, for it secretes no glue or hooks, but it stays where it is placed, and the fur hides it from sight. 

You release the moth into the cage again and it flutters around, agitated, singing an angry song while you creep away, hands sprinkled with moth dust. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Mindeye on Moth.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>268</ID>
      <DefaultText>You open the moth's cage and reach in with a towel. It batters you with frightened wings, but you manage to wrap it in the towel and part the fur at the back of its head and press the Mindeye against it's exposed carapace. The device adheres in a way you don't understand, for it secretes no glue or hooks, but it stays where it is placed, and the fur hides it from sight. 

You release the moth into the cage again and it flutters around, agitated, singing an angry song while you creep away, hands sprinkled with moth dust. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Mindeye on Moth.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>269</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>270</ID>
      <DefaultText>Waiting until both Veresterios and Lanalton have retired for the evening, you open the moth's cage and reach in with a towel. It batters you with frightened wings and bites you though the towel. You hiss and fall back, upsetting a stack of books.

There is movement in the hallway. Someone has heard you. You quickly close the cage door again, right the books, then creep away as the moth flutters around, agitated, singing an angry song. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>271</ID>
      <DefaultText>Once again you fail to catch the moth before someone approaches the room. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>272</ID>
      <DefaultText>Convince the other Nil to help you kill Aurigan.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>273</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Nil in the servants hall stare at you, shocked by your proposal. Many look over their shoulders. 

"Murder?" says Jaya, the housekeeper. "We'll all be killed."

"Rem has a plan," says Coi. "She's going to forge a suicide note. It'll look like Aurigan killed himself."

The Nil murmur anxiously, debating in whispers. 

Coi raises his voice. "We've been lucky so far. Only a few beatings and broken bones, but you know it won't last. Him or his Bayan will kill one of us eventually. Are you willing to just let it happen?"

After much more discussion, you and Coi manage to convince a group of ten to help you. The others don't like it, but would never betray a Nil to the masters. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Nil Agree to Help Kill Aurigan.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>274</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Nil in the servants hall stare at you, shocked by your proposal. Many look over their shoulders. 

"Murder?" says Jaya, the housekeeper. "We'll all be killed."

"Rem has a plan," says Coi. "She's going to forge a suicide note. It'll look like Aurigan killed himself."

The Nil murmur anxiously, debating in whispers. 

Coi raises his voice. "We've been lucky so far. Only a few beatings and broken bones, but you know it won't last. Him or his Bayan will kill one of us eventually. Are you willing to just let it happen?"

The Nil will not be convinced. They are too afraid. You're either going to have to attempt to kill Aurigan by yourself, or try another plan. 

{SCRIPT: Sets Global, Nil Won't Help Kill Aurigan.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>275</ID>
      <DefaultText>Leave the forged suicide note by Aurigan's bed.

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC has forged Suicide Note, and if PC is in Aurigan's Room.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>276</ID>
      <DefaultText>With Aurigan fast asleep, is the work of a moment to place the suicide note on his bedside table. Now all you have to do is wake him up and get him to chase you.

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Placed Suicide Note.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>277</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>278</ID>
      <DefaultText>For a week you wear the Mindeye, recording every moment of your life - the drudgery, the abuses, both minor and major, from your Sona masters and their Bayan enforcers. The slights, the insults, the shoves, the casual threats, the stories of the other Nil, the fear of losing your job, the fear of dying to keep it, your dreams of freedom, your rage, your sorrow, your infrequent joys, but because you read Another Man's Mirror, you are able to maintain a forgiving attitude through it all. 

Several times during the week, Aurigan accosts you, leering, joking, insulting you, making unwanted advances, threatening you with violence. You wonder how he'll react to being abused by himself.

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC read "Another Man's Mirror."}
{SCRIPT: Sets global, Wore the Mindeye.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>279</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I promise you," he says. "That will change. I have spent too long thinking only *I* had a mind, only I knew pain. My father's Nil need never fear me again. And you..." He raises his eyes to yours. "Who risked all to teach me this, I will have you as my teacher, my guide in the ways of an enlightened life, and together we will find a way to free the Nil from their bondage. We make Haref a city of freedom and equality at last."

As he bows to you, the walls of his room blur into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. Aurigan and the pink sky beyond his windows all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}
{SCRIPT: If PC read Another Man's Mirrow.}

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>280</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stay with him and dose him with haffa juice until it's time to take the Mindeye off again.

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC Has haffa juice.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>281</ID>
      <DefaultText>Though you fear he might wake, you ease Aurigan over on his back and pull gently on his chin, opening his mouth. This does not jar him out of his immersive dream, and you are able to dribble a bit of haffa juice into his mouth. He swallows it reflexively, and after a minute his twitching and moaning increases. He begins to whimper. 

A little while later, you hear Gurek return to his post outside the door, and you hide. He looks in on Aurigan, pauses as he sees him so restless, then shrugs and backs out again. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>282</ID>
      <DefaultText>After an hour you give Aurigan another few swallows of haffa juice, and once again his agitation grows worse, until he sits up in his bed, screaming, "The Nil are in my head! The Nil are in my head!"

Before you can try to silence him, Gurek slams through the door and looks around. Aurigan points directly at you. "It was her! She put the Nil in my head! I have to get them out! I have to--"

He sceams again and snatches a dagger from his bedside table, then races for the door. Gurek tries to stop him but Aurigan dodges around him, then calls back to him. "This way! To the servant's quarters! We'll start there!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>283</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>284</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>338</ID>
      <DefaultText>Returning to the library, you see Lanalton coming back from Veresterios' office. He sniffs when he sees that you haven't put away the pile of books. 

"Daydreaming again?" he asks. "Put shelve those books like I asked you too, and be quiet about it. Lord Veresterios is reading in his office, and I have work to do."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>339</ID>
      <DefaultText>Examine the singing moth.

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>340</ID>
      <DefaultText>The fist-sized moth chirrups and flutters at you as you approach. It is a beautiful thing from afar, with its crimson coat and beautiful wing markings, but its face is a bit unnerving. It has six eyes, widely spaced so that it can look in all directions at once, and the membrane behind its mandibles - the organ that allows it to sing - glistens and vibrates in a stomach-churning way. 

If it could talk, it would certainly have a lot to say, for it sees everything that goes on in the library, night and day. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>341</ID>
      <DefaultText>Read Eosus's Journal.
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>342</ID>
      <DefaultText>*"Do not attempt to view another's experiences while under the influence of stimulants, particularly at elevated viewing speeds. Tea, wakeleaf, haffa juice, all make it harder for the mind to accept the experiences of another mind as one's own, and this can lead to madness and death. Indeed, the best way to insure the sanity of the user is to administer small doses of intoxicants hourly until the viewing is complete."*</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>343</ID>
      <DefaultText>Go to Veresterios' office and talk to him about Aurigan. 
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>344</ID>
      <DefaultText>Learn that he won't punish Aurigan</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>345</ID>
      <DefaultText>Find Coi and talk to him.

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>346</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi swallows. "I don't know, Rem. That's... that's a big step, but..." His face flushes as anger suddenly overcomes him. "But, *yes!* After what he did to Dal. How can we not. We will help."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>347</ID>
      <DefaultText>Talk to Lanalton at his desk.



</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>348</ID>
      <DefaultText>He laughs. "That would be surest way to unemployment I could imagine. Verseterios is as kind a master as one could wish for, but he dotes on that boy and won't hear a word against him. The only thing that *might* turn him against him would be if Aurigan was fool enough to steal from the library."

He turns to you and his eyes soften. "Listen, girl. I know you've a stack of books hidden in the back closet. If you find that the pain of the world cannot be borne, go read them and escape. That's what they're for."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>349</ID>
      <DefaultText>Search for the books you stashed in the back closet. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>350</ID>
      <DefaultText>In a closet filled with mops and brooms, step ladders and chairs with missing legs, you find a stack of three bookmarked books, and also, hidden under it, some very incriminating pieces of paper. 

One piece of paper seems to be notes - written by you? - outlining various ways to remove Aurigan from Veresterios' house. The others are a note from Aurigan, written and signed by him, telling someone named Hekeria he never wants to see her again, and several pages of attempts - also by you? - to copy both Aurigan's handwriting and his signature. It seems you've been working on the problem of Aurigan for a while. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>351</ID>
      <DefaultText>Read the Laughing Jack

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>352</ID>
      <DefaultText>*Fynn laughed and tossed a pair of glittering gems on table. "Do you recognize these, madam?"*

*Lady Sommari stared. "Those are my dreaming jewels! Lost since last Chela's Day! Did you steal them, you bold rascal? I shall send for the levies!"*

*"Not I, madam," said Fynn. "But send for the levies nonetheless, for the thief is among us. Here is the proof." He threw down a pawn broker's note and pointed at the signature. "Do you know that scrawl?"*

*Lady Sommari gasped and turned to her son. "Imbruck! How could you! You are disinherited this instant!"*

*Beside him, Fora embraced Ran. "Oh, darling, I knew you would be lord of Sommari one day! And it's all thanks to the Laughing Jack!"*

{SCRIPT: Sets read the Laughing Jack conditional.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>353</ID>
      <DefaultText>Read the Jaws of Victory</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>354</ID>
      <DefaultText>*By the time we'd reached the Enstal line we'd had enough. The whole squad was in agreement, Hyrnhol had to go. He'd already got half of us killed in the Dool thanks to his cowardice and shilly-shallying, and his decision at Bresadt proved he hadn't gained any wisdom since. The only question was how to do it. Outright murder would get us all the chop, and the higher-ups were wise to the usual friendly-fire and "accidental" ordinance malfunction ploys. We had to be subtle.*  

*Then Gerrisae hit on it. We'd all heard Hyrnhal moaning about his wife leaving him, and so had the brass. If we wrote a note in his hand saying her betrayal had driven him to the brink, well, who'd gainsay it?*

{SCRIPT: Sets read the Jaws of Victory conditional.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>355</ID>
      <DefaultText>Read Another Man's Mirror</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>356</ID>
      <DefaultText>*The secret to peace is empathy. If we could all live for a time in our enemies' heads, and if they could live in ours, then conflict would be impossible, for they would understand our pain and we would understand theirs. Our life experiences would be shared. We would be family. Closer than family. We would be one. And who but a madman could make war upon himself?*

{SCRIPT: Sets read Another Man's Mirror conditional.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>357</ID>
      <DefaultText>Put books and notes away.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>358</ID>
      <DefaultText>You carefully hide the notes under the books and leave them as they were, then return to the library.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>359</ID>
      <DefaultText>Seek out Gurek and speak to him.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>360</ID>
      <DefaultText>Learn Gurek doesn't like Aurigan and wishes he was a better boss, or that he would fire him 

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>361</ID>
      <DefaultText>Learn Augian has dangerous gambling debts and is desperate for money</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>362</ID>
      <DefaultText>Learn that Gurek sometimes has to chase Aurigan's creditors away from the house.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>363</ID>
      <DefaultText>Start to put the banishment plan into action. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>364</ID>
      <DefaultText>Now that you've learned more about the Mindeye and gotten Gurek interested, your scheme can begin in earnest. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>365</ID>
      <DefaultText>Steal the Mindeye, which has a week in the life of a Nil recorded on it.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>366</ID>
      <DefaultText>Veresterios was very careful to lock the Mindeye in Lanalton's desk, but Lanalton is not very careful with the spare key. When he goes to the lavatory you easily unlock the desk drawer, take the Mindeye out, and relock the drawer, then place the spare key back where you found it. 

You then check the Mindeye. It does indeed have the life of a Nil recorded on it. The insults and degradations you see seem entirely familiar. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>367</ID>
      <DefaultText>Place the Mindeye on the singing moth.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>368</ID>
      <DefaultText>Waiting until both Veresterios and Lanalton have retired for the evening, you open the moth's cage and reach in with a towel. It batters you with frightened wings, but you manage to wrap it up and part the fur at the back of its head. Then you press the Mindeye against its exposed carapace. The device adheres in a way you don't understand, for it secretes no glue or hooks, but it stays where it is placed, and the fur hides it from sight. 

You release the moth into the cage again and it flutters around, agitated, singing an angry song while you creep away, hands sprinkled with moth dust. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>369</ID>
      <DefaultText>Go see Gurek and ask him to do his part. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>370</ID>
      <DefaultText>A spark of hope glimmers in the big man's eye. "This is a good plan. Aurigan'll jump at the chance to pay off the shin men. And if this gets me free of him, I'll owe you forever."

He stands. "I'll go tell him."
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>371</ID>
      <DefaultText>Find Lanalton and Veresterios once you know Aurigan has stolen the diary.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>372</ID>
      <DefaultText>""</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>373</ID>
      <DefaultText>Try another path. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>374</ID>
      <DefaultText>You pause to think things through. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>375</ID>
      <DefaultText>Start to put the murder plan into action. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>376</ID>
      <DefaultText>With the suicide note in your pocket, there's only a few more steps and Aurigan will trouble you no more. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>377</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell the Nil your plan to murder Aurigan, and ask for their help. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>378</ID>
      <DefaultText>Most of the Nil in the servants hall nod as you ask for help, but some are still not on board. There is much murmuring.

"Murder?" says Jaya, the housekeeper. "We'll all be killed."

"Not with Rem's plan," says Coi. "You heard her. She's going to forge a suicide note. It'll look like Aurigan killed himself." He raises his voice over the heated debate. "He's already had his Bayan throw one of us down the Bore. How many more have to die before you're ready to stop him?"

After much discussion, you and Coi manage to convince a group of ten to help you, and the others grudingly go along.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>379</ID>
      <DefaultText>Get Gurek to leave Aurigan's door by telling him there's a shin man at the front door asking for Aurigan.
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>380</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek grunts, then uncrosses his arms and stands. "I told those thumb-breakers never to come here again. Excuse me."

He walks in the direction of the stairs. There's nothing between you and Aurigan's door. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>381</ID>
      <DefaultText>Leave your suicide note by Aurigan's bed. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>382</ID>
      <DefaultText>You open Aurigan's door and enter a large, luxurious room, with a lessened-gravity bed hovering in one corner and beautiful works of art on the walls. There are also underclothes and dirty cups and plates scattered across the floor. The place is a mess.

Aurigan snores in the bed, dead to the world. You sneak to his bedside table and place the suicide note with no difficulty. Now all you have to do is wake him up and get him to chase you.
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>383</ID>
      <DefaultText>Put the Mindeye on Aurigan.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>384</ID>
      <DefaultText>You open Aurigan's door and enter a large, luxurious room, with a lessened-gravity bed hovering in one corner and beautiful works of art on the walls. There are also underclothes and dirty cups and plates scattered across the floor. The place is a mess.

Aurigan snores in the bed, face down and dead to the world. Now all you have to do is place the Mindeye behind his ear. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>385</ID>
      <DefaultText>Get Aurigan to chase you.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>386</ID>
      <DefaultText>""</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>387</ID>
      <DefaultText>Start to put the empathy plan into action. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>388</ID>
      <DefaultText>You've got the Mindeye, and it has a week in the life of a Nil recorded within it. Time to show Aurigan how the other half lives. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>389</ID>
      <DefaultText>Search the kitchen for alcohol or stimulants.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>390</ID>
      <DefaultText>""</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>391</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>392</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>393</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>394</ID>
      <DefaultText>A passage on the bookmarked page has been set off with faint pencil marks. It reads:</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>395</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>396</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>397</ID>
      <DefaultText>A line has been drawn next to a few paragraphs on the bookmarked page. They read:</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>398</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>399</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>400</ID>
      <DefaultText>A short section of the bookmarked page has been bracketed with faint lines. It reads:</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>401</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>409</ID>
      <DefaultText>Skimming the expensive book, you learn how to operate the Mindeye, including how to speed it up so that a day's experience can be viewed in a single hour, or a week's in one night. 

You also learn some of the dangers of using the device, and how to mitigate them, including this:</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>410</ID>
      <DefaultText>Read the notes you made before.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>411</ID>
      <DefaultText>The page reads...

Banishment?

-Trick A into stealing books 
-Prove to V that A is thief
-But how?
-Mindeye?
-Moth?
-Gurek? 
-Bring evidence to L? V?

Death?

-Fake A's suicide
-How?
-Write note
-Make G go away?
-Leave note
-Push A off balcony?
-Too strong, need help


Enlightenment?

-Make Aurigan better person
-How?
-Empathy? Show him Nil life?
-Mindeye?
-Is it enough?
-Percautions?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>412</ID>
      <DefaultText>Read suicide note. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>413</ID>
      <DefaultText>""</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>414</ID>
      <DefaultText>You sneak out of the library and knock softly at the open door of Veresterios'  office. He looks up from his desk and smiles. "Yes, girl. What is it? Does Lanalton want me?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>415</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Your son just had his Bayan servant kill a Nil by dropping him into the Bore."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>416</ID>
      <DefaultText>He frowns. "And you feel this is unjust, do you? Well, then I would take it up with Aurigan's servant, since it was he who killed your friend, eh?"

He turns back to his writing. "Even if Aurigan gave the order, Gurek did not have to obey it. He is a servant, not a slave, you know, just like you. If you wish to risk unemployment, you may disobey me at any time. Now run along, won't you? There's a good girl."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>417</ID>
      <DefaultText>"The death is still Aurigan's fault. You must tell him to stop."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>418</ID>
      <DefaultText>He looks up again, eyes sharp this time. "You are making demands of me? I consider myself a very lenient employer, my dear, but I will not be spoken to in that manner by a servant. If you do it again, Lanalton will be looking for a new assistant. Now do not disturb me further."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>419</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you walk from Veresterios' office, the wood paneled hallway blurs into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>420</ID>
      <DefaultText>"If any more Nil die, it will be your fault." </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>421</ID>
      <DefaultText>He looks up again, eyes sharp this time. "You would blame me for the deaths I am not even aware of? I consider myself a very lenient employer, my dear, but I will not be spoken to in that manner by a servant.  If you do it again, Lanalton will be looking for a new assistant. Now do not disturb me further."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>422</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Thank you, sir. I'll go now."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>423</ID>
      <DefaultText>He waves, only half listening. "Yes yes. Carry on."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>424</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Your son just cost you money and property by ordering his Bayan to kill one of your household servants."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>425</ID>
      <DefaultText>He frowns. "You make a good point. Thanks for bringing the situation to my attention."

He turns back to his writing. "I shall speak to him when I can. In the meantime I would advise you to tell your little friends to be on their best behavior so that further incidents do not occur. Now run along, won't you? There's a good girl."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>426</ID>
      <DefaultText>Excuse yourself.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>427</ID>
      <DefaultText>The librarian sighs as he senses you standing at his shoulder. "Didn't I say I didn't want to be disturbed? What is it?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>428</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Lord Aurigan just had his Bayan, Gurek, kill a Nil by dropping him into the bore. Is there nothing we can do?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>429</ID>
      <DefaultText>He nods, but doesn't look up. "I sympathize, girl. The boy is a spoiled brat with the morals of a ravage bear. But he is the master's son, so we must bear it until he leaves us again, may the makers grant it be soon."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>430</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Would you be willing to talk to Veresterios about Aurigan, sir?" </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>432</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Would you be willing to help me find a way to deal with Aurigan?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>433</ID>
      <DefaultText>He looks up at you, eyes wide with fear. "What are you saying, girl? Deal with him? In what way?"

He waves hands, frantic. "No no no, don't tell me! I don't want to hear. And if I do hear, I'm telling Veresterios, you understand me? You can't go around threatening the master's son! Now, leave me alone. I have no time for nonsense."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>438</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Thank you. Excuse me."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>439</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Mmm, yes. Back to work."

He returns to his work.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>440</ID>
      <DefaultText>You slip out of the library and find Coi and his crew polishing the floor of a wide hallway. He gives you a hopeful look. 

"Have you thought of something?" he asks.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>441</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Do you know anything we can use against Aurigan?" </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>442</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi shakes his head. "I wish I did, but he's been away in the Steadfast since he was twelve. I know nothing about who he is now." He shivers. "I'm sure Gurek could tell you, if you dared ask."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>443</ID>
      <DefaultText>"What do you think about getting Veresterios to kick Aurigan out of the house?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>444</ID>
      <DefaultText>He beams. "That would be wonderful, but I don't know what would do the trick. The old man is as blind as a cave crab when it comes to his son's faults."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>445</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Do you think we could get away with killing Aurigan?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>446</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi looks around to see if anybody heard, then whispers. "He certainly deserves it, but there would be one hell of a skist storm afterward, wouldn't there? We'd all get the chop for certain. No Nil in the house would survive."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>447</ID>
      <DefaultText>Will you help me kill Aurigan if I can make sure the Nil won't be blamed?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>449</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>450</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>451</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>452</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>453</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Do you think it's possible to make Aurigan a nicer person?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>454</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi laughs, then claps his hand over his mouth and looks around the silent corridor. 

"I think you'd have an easier time of it trying to pull a juriskar through a drainpipe by the tail," he whispers. "That boy is mean all the way down to the bone. As cold as a fish cutter's knife."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>455</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Thanks. Take care."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>456</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi nods and waves. "Thanks, Rem. We're counting on you."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>457</ID>
      <DefaultText>You find Gurek shaking his craggy head and muttering to himself on a bench outside Aurigan's apartments. His massive gray-skinned arms bulge as he smacks one skull-sized fist into the other. He looks up as you approach.

"What d'you want?" he asks. His voice sounds like stone wheels crushing bones.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>458</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Why did you kill Dal?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>459</ID>
      <DefaultText>He glares at you for a long time, then grunts. "I need my job, just like you need yours. Though..." He shifts, uncomfortable. "Though you might like yours better."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>460</ID>
      <DefaultText>"So why kill to keep a job you don't like?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>461</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek growls. "I get fired for disobeying orders, the Sona put me on the 'difficult' list, and I don't get another job. Same thing if I quit. And if I snap that nasty little grub's neck like he deserves, I get the big drop. Unless you got some idea how to make the boss a better person, or get me out clean, I don't got a lot of options."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>462</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Why is Aurigan so cruel?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>463</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek snorts. "He's deep in debt. All he's done since we've been back is go to the gaming house and lose at tiles. That's why he's always so angry. He's desperate."

"I'll die protecting him from the shin men one night, I guarantee it." He sighs. "Might be a blessing."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>464</ID>
      <DefaultText>"If I found a way to get Aurigan disinherited, would you help?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>465</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek raises one heavy brow. "You got a scheme? Hmmm. As long as you leave me clean enough to get another job when he's gone, I'm all for it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>466</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Would you help kill Aurigan?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>467</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek turns and looks at you straight on. "Don't have much love for the boss, but he doesn't die on my watch, understand?" He cracks his knuckles. "I hear you're planning something, I go to Veresterios. You make your move, I kill you."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>468</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Farewell."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>469</ID>
      <DefaultText>He gives you a nod. "So long."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>470</ID>
      <DefaultText>Ask him why he would agree to kill a fellow servant.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>471</ID>
      <DefaultText>He ponders this for a long time, then grunts. "Why don't you talk back to that snotty librarian?" He shifts, uncomfortable. "I know. It's not the same, but I need this job, no matter what I think of it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>472</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell him you were just passing by. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>473</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Then keep walking," he says.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>474</ID>
      <DefaultText>It won't be easy. You'll have to trick Aurigan into stealing the Diary of Eosus, and then prove to Veresterios that his son was the thief. 

To do this, you'll need to put the Mindeye on the singing moth so it will record the theft. Then you'll need to convince Gurek to suggest to Aurigan that the book could cover his gambling debts and make him a fortune as well. But if Aurigan is kicked out, Gurek loses his job, so the easiest way to get the Bayan's cooperation is to find him a new employer. 

Finally, once you've got the evidence you need, you'll have to tell Veresterios about the theft. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>475</ID>
      <DefaultText>Find Gurek a new employer</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>476</ID>
      <DefaultText>Speaking with Coi, you think you can use the servant's grapevine to find Gurek a more suitable employer, but it may take time, and who knows what terror Aurigan might inflict upon the servants while you wait for an answer. On the other hand, Gurek will be much more helpful if you can assure him he will have a job after Aurigan is thrown out. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>477</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take your time and try to find Gurek the best employer you can.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>478</ID>
      <DefaultText>After a week of searching, wheedling, and outright bribery, you find the perfect job for Gurek. A feeble old Sona needs a patient and able-bodied Bayan to help him move from room to room in his overlarge house. Gurek won't have to hurt anyone against his will ever again.

Unfortunately, while you searched, Aurigan broke Coi's collar bone by shoving him down the stairs, and blackened the eyes of a maid. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Rem has found Gurek a Job.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>479</ID>
      <DefaultText>Call in every favor and try to find Gurek a new employer within two days. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>480</ID>
      <DefaultText>You have strained Mer's friendships to the limit, and put her in debt with bribes she could not afford, but you managed to find a better job for Gurek - guardian at a grain warehouse. It's not an interesting job, but it also doesn't involve hurting innocent people. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Rem has found Gurek a Job.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>481</ID>
      <DefaultText>You strained Mer's friendships to the limit, and put her in debt with bribes she could not afford, but still could not conjure up a job for Gurek. Maybe a longer search might yield results. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>482</ID>
      <DefaultText>Forget about finding Gurek a new employer. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>483</ID>
      <DefaultText>You turn your focus to other tasks. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>484</ID>
      <DefaultText>Try again to find Gurek a new employer. 

{SCRIPT: Only appears once 114 plays once.)</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>485</ID>
      <DefaultText>Steal the Mindeye.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: Does not appear if this step was completed in another plan.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>486</ID>
      <DefaultText>Veresterios was very careful to lock the Mindeye in Lanalton's desk, but Lanalton is not very careful with the spare key. When he goes to the lavatory you easily unlock the desk drawer, take the Mindeye out, and relock the drawer, then place the spare key back where you found it. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Rem has the Mindeye}
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>487</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>488</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>489</ID>
      <DefaultText>Waiting until both Veresterios and Lanalton have retired for the evening, you open the moth's cage and reach in with a towel. It batters you with frightened wings, but you manage to wrap it in the towel and part the fur at the back of its head and press the Mindeye against it's exposed carapace. The device adheres in a way you don't understand, for it secretes no glue or hooks, but it stays where it is placed, and the fur hides it from sight. 

You release the moth into the cage again and it flutters around, agitated, singing an angry song while you creep away, hands sprinkled with moth dust. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Mindeye on Moth.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>490</ID>
      <DefaultText>You open the moth's cage and reach in with a towel. It batters you with frightened wings, but you manage to wrap it in the towel and part the fur at the back of its head and press the Mindeye against it's exposed carapace. The device adheres in a way you don't understand, for it secretes no glue or hooks, but it stays where it is placed, and the fur hides it from sight. 

You release the moth into the cage again and it flutters around, agitated, singing an angry song while you creep away, hands sprinkled with moth dust. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Mindeye on Moth.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>491</ID>
      <DefaultText />
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>492</ID>
      <DefaultText>Waiting until both Veresterios and Lanalton have retired for the evening, you open the moth's cage and reach in with a towel. It batters you with frightened wings and bites you though the towel. You hiss and fall back, upsetting a stack of books.

There is movement in the hallway. Someone has heard you. You quickly close the cage door again, right the books, then creep away as the moth flutters around, agitated, singing an angry song. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>493</ID>
      <DefaultText>Once again you fail to catch the moth before someone approaches the room. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>494</ID>
      <DefaultText>Place the Mindeye on the singing moth. 

{SCRIPT: Does not play if Rem doesn't have the Mindeye.}
{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT:Can be tried multiple times. Easier after the first time.}
{SCRIPT: Does not play if the Mindeye is already on the Moth.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>495</ID>
      <DefaultText>Try again to place the Mindeye on the singing moth. 

{SCRIPT: Does not play if Rem doesn't have the Mindeye.}
{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT:Can be tried multiple times. Easier after the first time.}
{SCRIPT: Does not play if the Mindeye is already on the Moth.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>496</ID>
      <DefaultText>Tell Gurek you found him a job, and get him to tell Aurigan about the Diary of Eosus.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: This version only plays if you got Gurek a job.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>497</ID>
      <DefaultText>A spark of hope glimmers in the big man's eyes. "You found me job? Good. Then I'll do it. I'll tell Aurigan about the book. He'll jump at the chance to pay off the shin men. Be ready."

{SCRIPT: Sets a global "Gurek tells Aurigan about Book"}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>498</ID>
      <DefaultText>Convince Gurek to tell Aurigan about the Diary of Eosus.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: This version plays if you did not get Gurek a job.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>499</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek stares at you, eyes dull. "I'm gonna lose my job over this. But maybe it's time. I'm sick of breaking arms." He nods. "Okay. I'll tell him about the book. He'll jump at the chance to pay off the shin men. Be ready."

{SCRIPT: Sets a global "Gurek tells Aurigan about Book"}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>500</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek shakes his massive head. "I know you're trying to save your people, but I gotta live too. You get the boss thrown out, I'm out of a job. Sorry. Find me a place to land, maybe we can talk."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>501</ID>
      <DefaultText>Work on another plan.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>502</ID>
      <DefaultText>You turn your focus to a different task.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>503</ID>
      <DefaultText>Wait until Aurigan has stolen the Diary of Eosus, then take the final step by telling Veresterios and Lanalton that the book is missing and you might be able to expose the thief.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>504</ID>
      <DefaultText>You're not ready. The plan won't succeed unless all the pieces are in place. Have another look at it, or maybe try another plan. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>505</ID>
      <DefaultText>The men stare at you, stunned, then Lanalton snarls. "You lying runt! I don't believe you! It must be here!"

"Aye," says Veresterios. "Find it!"

Though you know it's pointless, you help them search the shelves and tables. You find nothing. 

Veresterios turns on you. "You said you know who did this? Who was it?"

You tell him that, having recently suspected intruders in the library, you put the Mindeye on the singing moth in the hope it might see who was skuling around. 

"How dare you use such a valuable device without permission!" shouts Lanalton. "You shall be whipped!"

"Never mind about that," says Veresterios. "Bring me the device. I must see!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>506</ID>
      <DefaultText>With careful hands, Lanalton takes the Mindeye off the moth and hands it to Veresterios. The old sona puts it to his eye and twists it to speed up the viewing. For a long time, he just watches, then he stops it, twists it back and watches a short section again. His face sags and he lowers the Mindeye to his lap. 

"Lanalton," he says. "Send for my son."

A few moments later, Aurigan slouches into the library, looking put out, with Gurek behind him. "What is it?" he asks. "I was busy."

Veresterios shakes his head. "I have forgiven you much, Aurigan. Blamed much on your youth. But that you would steal from your own father. That is too much. You are no longer my son."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>507</ID>
      <DefaultText>"What!" says Aurigan. "Who says I've stolen from you? They're a liar!"

Veresterios holds out the Mindeye. "Put it to your eye and twist it one click to the right. You will see he who has condemned you."

Aurigan snatches the device from his father's hand, then watches it. A moment later his jaw drops, and he flings it from him. "How...? How...?"

Veresterios indicates you. "Rem put it on the moth. It saw all."

Aurigan turns on you, shaking. "You. You did this for vengeance, didn't you? Because I threatened your grubby little friends. Well, I'll kill you for it. It's the Bore for you, you little tattle tale!"

He charges you, eyes crazed, hands extended.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>508</ID>
      <DefaultText>Fight Aurigan. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>509</ID>
      <DefaultText>You swing for Aurigan's jaw, but he swats your fist aside and throws you over his shoulder, then strides for the balcony. There is nothing you can do. He is far stronger than you. Your struggles are futile.

Then, out of the corner of your eye, you see Veresterios raise a device like a pen. A green light blinds you and you are on the ground, twitching beside Aurigan, who is doing the same. 

Veresterios stands over his son. "I see now you are everything the Nil said you were. Gurek, remove this trash from my house, and take the girl too. She was brave to bring this villainy to my attention, but she swung at Aurigan just now, and striking a Sona is forbidden. She'll have to go."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>510</ID>
      <DefaultText>As Gurek hauls you to your feet, he and Veresterios and Lanalton all blur into a red haze around you, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>511</ID>
      <DefaultText>Flee Aurigan.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>512</ID>
      <DefaultText>You turn and run, but Aurigan catches you in a step and throws you over his shoulder, then strides for the balcony. There is nothing you can do. He is far stronger than you. Your struggles are futile.

Then, out of the corner of your eye, you see Veresterios raise a device like a pen. A green light blinds you and you are on the ground, twitching beside Aurigan, who is doing the same. 

Veresterios stands over his son. "I see now you are everything the Nil said you were. Gurek, remove this trash from my house, and help the girl to her feet. Though she tried to flee, she will still be rewarded for bringing this villainy to my attention."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>513</ID>
      <DefaultText>As Gurek lowers his giant hand to your small one and helps you stand, he and Veresterios and Lanalton all blur into a red haze around you, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>514</ID>
      <DefaultText>Quote the Laughing Jack and make a witty retort. 

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC read The Laughing Jack.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>515</ID>
      <DefaultText>Aurigan frowns as he catches you and throws you over his shoulder. "Who are you calling a ner-do-well?"

You struggle, but he is much stronger than you, and cutting remarks won't help you as he strides for the balcony. Then, out of the corner of your eye, you see Veresterios raise a device like a pen. A green light blinds you and you are on the ground, twitching beside Aurigan, who is doing the same. 

Veresterios stands over his son. "I see now you are everything the Nil said you were. Gurek, remove this trash from my house, and help the girl to her feet. Despite insulting my son, she will still be rewarded for bringing this villainy to my attention."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>516</ID>
      <DefaultText>As Gurek lowers his giant hand to your small one and helps you stand, he and Veresterios and Lanalton all blur into a red haze around you, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>517</ID>
      <DefaultText>Offer no resistance.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>518</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you sink to your knees in submission, Aurigan catches you and throws you over his shoulder, then strides for the balcony. There is nothing you can do. He is far stronger than you. Your struggles are futile.

Then, out of the corner of your eye, you see Veresterios raise a device like a pen. A green light blinds you and you are on the ground, twitching beside Aurigan, who is doing the same. 

Veresterios stands over his son. "I see now you are everything the Nil said you were. Gurek, remove this trash from my house, and help the girl to her feet. She will be rewarded for bringing this villainy to my attention."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>519</ID>
      <DefaultText>As Gurek lowers his giant hand to your small one and helps you stand, he and Veresterios and Lanalton all blur into a red haze around you, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>520</ID>
      <DefaultText>Killing Aurigan shouldn't be too difficult, but killing him without implicating yourself or any of the other Nil is going to be tricky. 

Tricking Veresterios into thinking Aurigan commited suicide by jumping off the balcony seems like a viable plan, but pulling it off will require several steps. First, you'll need to convince the other Nil to help you, because he's too big to push over yourself. Second, you'll need to forge a suicide note. Third, you have to get Gurek away from Aurigan's door so you can sneak in and leave the note, then get him to chase you to the balcony where the other Nil will be waiting. 

Then all you'll have to do is push. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>521</ID>
      <DefaultText>Use a stirring speech from "Jaws of Victory" to convince other Nil to help kill Aurigan.

{SCRIPT: Free pass if the PC has read Jaws of Victory.}
{SCRIPT: Does not play if global, Nil Won't Help Kill Aurigan has been set.}
{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>522</ID>
      <DefaultText>Most of the Nil in the servants hall nod as you finish your speech, moved, but some are still not on board. There is much murmuring.

"Murder?" says Jaya, the housekeeper. "We'll all be killed."

"Not with Rem's plan," says Coi. "You heard her. She's going to forge a suicide note. It'll look like Aurigan killed himself." He raises his voice over the heated debate. "We've been lucky so far. Only a few beatings and broken bones, but you know it won't last. Him or his Bayan will kill one of us eventually. Are you willing to just let it happen?"

After much discussion, you and Coi manage to convince a group of ten to help you, and the others grudingly go along.

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Nil Agree to Help Kill Aurigan.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>523</ID>
      <DefaultText>Convince the other Nil to help you kill Aurigan.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>524</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Nil in the servants hall stare at you, shocked by your proposal. Many look over their shoulders. 

"Murder?" says Jaya, the housekeeper. "We'll all be killed."

"Rem has a plan," says Coi. "She's going to forge a suicide note. It'll look like Aurigan killed himself."

The Nil murmur anxiously, debating in whispers. 

Coi raises his voice. "We've been lucky so far. Only a few beatings and broken bones, but you know it won't last. Him or his Bayan will kill one of us eventually. Are you willing to just let it happen?"

After much more discussion, you and Coi manage to convince a group of ten to help you. The others don't like it, but would never betray a Nil to the masters. 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Nil Agree to Help Kill Aurigan.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>525</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Nil in the servants hall stare at you, shocked by your proposal. Many look over their shoulders. 

"Murder?" says Jaya, the housekeeper. "We'll all be killed."

"Rem has a plan," says Coi. "She's going to forge a suicide note. It'll look like Aurigan killed himself."

The Nil murmur anxiously, debating in whispers. 

Coi raises his voice. "We've been lucky so far. Only a few beatings and broken bones, but you know it won't last. Him or his Bayan will kill one of us eventually. Are you willing to just let it happen?"

The Nil will not be convinced. They are too afraid. You're either going to have to attempt to kill Aurigan by yourself, or try another plan. 

{SCRIPT: Sets Global, Nil Won't Help Kill Aurigan.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>526</ID>
      <DefaultText>Forge Aurigan's suicide note.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>527</ID>
      <DefaultText>The hardest part of the forgery is finding samples of Aurigan's writing to learn from. He doesn't write much. Finally, however, you discover a notebook from his travels that he left in the library, and you begin. 

Two days later, after staying up late each night, practicing with stolen pen and paper, you feel you have the idiosyncracies of his style down pat and you write and sign a simple note. "Forgive me, Father. I cannot face my debts or the shame I have brought to my family. This is the end." 

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Suicide Note Written.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>528</ID>
      <DefaultText>Try to trick Gurek into leaving Aurigan's door by telling him there is someone disreputable at the front door asking for Aurigan.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: Sets global, Tried to Trick Gurek into Leaving.}
{SCRIPT: Does not play if you've tried to trick Gurek into leaving before.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>529</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek grunts, then uncrosses his arms and stands. "I told that thumb-breaker never to come here. Excuse me."

He walks in the direction of the stairs.

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Got Gurek Away From Door.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>530</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek shrugs. "Tell the Bayan downstairs to deal with him. He's not worth my time, and I'm sure not waking the boss about it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>531</ID>
      <DefaultText>Sneak into Aurigan's room.

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC Got Gurek Away From Door.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>532</ID>
      <DefaultText>With Gurek out of the way, entering Aurigan's room is as simple as opening the door.

It is a large, luxurious room, with a lessened-gravity bed hovering in one corner and beautiful works of art on the walls. There are also underclothes and dirty cups and plates scattered across the floor. The place is a mess.

Aurigan snores in the bed, dead to the world. 

{SCRIPT: Sets Global, In Aurigan's Room.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>533</ID>
      <DefaultText>Leave the forged suicide note by Aurigan's bed.

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC has forged Suicide Note, and if PC is in Aurigan's Room.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>534</ID>
      <DefaultText>With Aurigan fast asleep, is the work of a moment to place the suicide note on his bedside table. Now all you have to do is wake him up and get him to chase you.

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Placed Suicide Note.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>535</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take final step in your plan to murder Aurigan by tricking him into chasing you to the balcony.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>536</ID>
      <DefaultText>You're not ready. The plan won't succeed unless all the pieces are in place. Have another look at it, or maybe try another plan. 

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC has not placed the suicide note or hasn't recruited the other Nil}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>537</ID>
      <DefaultText>You slap Aurigan across the face. It takes several more to wake him up, but finally he sits up and looks around with bleary eyes. 

"Who's hitting me?" he asks.

Then he sees you, and his eyes narrow. "Did you just-"

You slap him again and he roars up out of the covers, dressed only in his undergarments. "Impertinent slut! I'll kill you for this!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>538</ID>
      <DefaultText>He leaps unsteadily at you, and you dart for the door. He stumbles after, snarling. "Come back here! Do you think this is a game? Gurek! Gurek, where are you?"

You run out the door and he follows, trying to catch his breath enough to shout, and you soon lead him to the balcony, where he stops, weaving and wheezing, and stares at the ten assembled Nil. 

"What is this?" he asks. "A party? Are you all star gazing?"

The Nil stare back at him, hesitating. You can see the fear in their eyes now that they're faced with the reality of the plan. It looks like they might run. 

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>539</ID>
      <DefaultText>Rally the Nil to push Aurigan, and start pushing Aurigan yourself. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>540</ID>
      <DefaultText>At your urging, the Nil join you, quickly and silently surrounding Aurigan and shoving him toward the edge.

"What are you doing?" he squawks. "Let go of me this instant!"

As momentum forces Aurigan closer to the balustrade, he grabs you and tries to use you as a weapon against the others. It doesn't work, and he starts tipping backwards over the balustrade - and taking you with him. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>541</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi doesn't allow it. As Aurigan topples over the edge, Coi pulls you from his arms and sets you on the balcony floor, hugging you while the falling Sona's screams echo up from the Core. 

"You did it!" says Coi. "You saved us. We can't thank you enough."

But as the Nil begin to disperse, a coldness comes over you. You have ended a man's life tonight. Was it the best way to help your friends, or just the easiest?

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>542</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you start back through the library, the walls around you blur into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The books, the moonlight, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness, but the questions in your heart still remain. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>543</ID>
      <DefaultText>Rally the Nil to push Aurigan, but don't help. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>544</ID>
      <DefaultText>At your urging, the Nil quickly and silently surround Aurigan and shove him toward the edge.

"What are you doing?" he squawks. "Let go of me this instant!"

As momentum forces Aurigan closer to the balustrade, he grabs Coi and tries to use him as a weapon against the others. It doesn't work, and he starts tipping backwards over the balustrade - and taking Coi with him. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>545</ID>
      <DefaultText>The Nil try to pull Coi from Aurigan's arms but the Sona topples over the edge before they can get him free. Aurigan and Coi fall into the Core together, screaming as they drop. 

The assembled Nil stare after them for a long time, then slowly and quietly begin to disperse. None of them look at you. 

You too look into the abyss. You freed the Nil from Aurigan's tyranny, but at the cost of Coi's life. Was it worth the trade? Should you have done more to help? Should you have found another way?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>546</ID>
      <DefaultText>Keep quiet and try to push Aurigan over yourself. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>547</ID>
      <DefaultText>Your solitary attack on Aurigan inspires the others to come forward, and they start helping you shove him toward the edge.

Unfortunately, he's got a good grip on you, and uses you as weapon to knock the others back. Your struggling, however, throws him off balance, and he falls against the balustrade. A pair of Nil see this as an opening and rush in to slam into his shoulder. 

Aurigan looses his footing and topples over the edge... taking you with him. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>548</ID>
      <DefaultText>Coi screams and nearly throws himself over the rail to grab at you, but he's too late, and you see his horrified face receding above you as you fall, the walls of the Bore closing in and Aurigan shrieking in your ear. 

You freed the Nil from his tyranny at the cost of your own life - and Aurigan's. Was it the best way? Or was there another way where no one had to die?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>549</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you plummet deeper and deeper into the Bore, the gantries and catwalks you fall past begin to blur into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. Aurigan, the Bore, all of Haref vanishes into silent darkness, but the questions in your heart still remain. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>550</ID>
      <DefaultText>Making Aurigan a better person is the noblest plan, but it won't be easy, and it could lead to driving him mad if the proper steps aren't taken - even if they are. 

First, you'll need to steal the Mindeye and wear it for a week, recording all your waking and sleeping moments. Then you'll have to get Gurek away from Aurigan's room so you can sneak in and place the Mindeye behind Aurigan's ear, forcing him to experience a week's worth of being a Nil in a single night. And if you want to keep him from going mad, you'll have to dose him with alcohol once every hour and hope it's enough. 

Otherwise he might end up a gibbering lunatic and you wouldn't want that - or would you?</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>551</ID>
      <DefaultText>Steal the Mindeye.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: Does not appear if this step was completed in another plan.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>552</ID>
      <DefaultText>Veresterios was very careful to lock the Mindeye in Lanalton's desk, but Lanalton is not very careful with the spare key. When he goes to the lavatory you easily unlock the desk drawer, take the Mindeye out, and relock the drawer, then place the spare key back where you found it. 

{SCRIPT: Rem has the Mindeye}
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>553</ID>
      <DefaultText>Acquire alcohol to mitigate the madness-inducing effects of the Mindeye.

{SCRIPT: Doesn't play if 245 has played: Acquire stimulants to increase the madness-inducing effects of the Mindeye. }</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>554</ID>
      <DefaultText>Rummaging through the pantry you come up with plenty of alcohol, and also a small bottle of stimulating haffa juice. It would be easy to steal either. Or both. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>555</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take the alcohol. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>556</ID>
      <DefaultText>You slip a small bottle of wine into your servant's tunic. No one notices. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>557</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take the haffa juice.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>558</ID>
      <DefaultText>You slip the bottle of haffa juice into your servant's tunic. No one notices. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>559</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take both.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>560</ID>
      <DefaultText>You slip a bottle of wine and a bottle of haffa juice into your servant's tunic. You slosh a bit when you walk, but no one notices. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>561</ID>
      <DefaultText>Acquire stimulants to increase the madness-inducing effects of the Mindeye. 

{SCRIPT: Doesn't play if 127 has played: Acquire alcohol to mitigate the madness-inducing effects of the Mindeye.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>562</ID>
      <DefaultText>Use the Mindeye to record a week of being a Nil.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: This does not play if PC has not stolen Mindeye.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>563</ID>
      <DefaultText>For a week you wear the Mindeye, recording every moment of your life - the drudgery, the abuses, both minor and major, from your Sona masters and their Bayan enforcers. The slights, the insults, the shoves, the casual threats, the stories of the other Nil, the fear of losing your job, the fear of dying to keep it, your dreams of freedom, your rage, your sorrow, your infrequent joys, but because you read Another Man's Mirror, you are able to maintain a forgiving attitude through it all. 

Several times during the week, Aurigan accosts you, leering, joking, insulting you, making unwanted advances, threatening you with violence. You wonder how he'll react to being abused by himself.

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC read "Another Man's Mirror."}
{SCRIPT: Sets global, Wore the Mindeye.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>564</ID>
      <DefaultText>For a week you wear the Mindeye behind your ear, recording every moment of your life - the drudgery, the abuses, both minor and major, from your Sona masters and their Bayan enforcers. The slights, the insults, the shoves, the casual threats, the stories of the other Nil, the fear of losing your job, the fear of dying to keep it, your dreams of freedom, your rage, your sorrow, your infrequent joys, your courage, your cowardice, your pettiness, your simple humanity. 

Several times during the week, Aurigan accosts you, leering, joking, insulting you, making unwanted advances, threatening you with violence. You wonder how he will react to being abused by himself.

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Wore the Mindeye.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>565</ID>
      <DefaultText>Trick Gurek into leaving Aurigan's door by telling him there is someone disreputable at the front door asking for Aurigan.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: Sets global, Tried to Trick Gurek into Leaving.}
{SCRIPT: Does not play if you've tried to trick Gurek into leaving before.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>566</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek grunts, then uncrosses his arms and stands. "I told that thumb-breaker never to come here. Excuse me."

He walks in the direction of the stairs.

{SCRIPT: Sets global, Got Gurek Away From Door.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>567</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek shrugs. "Tell the Bayan downstairs to deal with him. He's not worth my time, and I'm sure not waking the boss about it."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>568</ID>
      <DefaultText>Sneak into Aurigan's room.

{SCRIPT: This step is crucial. The plan will not succeed without completing it successfully.}
{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC Got Gurek Away From Door.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>569</ID>
      <DefaultText>With Gurek out of the way, entering Aurigan's room is as simple as opening the door.

It is a large, luxurious room, with a lessened-gravity bed hovering in one corner and beautiful works of art on the walls. There are also underclothes and dirty cups and plates scattered across the floor. The place is a mess.

Aurigan snores in the bed, face down and dead to the world. It would be the work of a moment to to place the Mindeye behind his ear. 

{SCRIPT: Sets Global, In Aurigan's Room.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>570</ID>
      <DefaultText>Take the final step to make Aurigan a better person. Put Mindeye on Aurigan.

{SCRIPT: Only playa if PC is In Aurigan's Room.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>571</ID>
      <DefaultText>You're not ready. The plan won't succeed unless all the pieces are in place. Have another look at it, or maybe try another plan. 

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC does not have the Mindeye, or has not Worn the Mindeye, or both.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>572</ID>
      <DefaultText>Are you sure you want to this without having any alcohol on hand to help him mitigate the effects of the Mindeye? Without it, the posibility that he could go mad is quite high. 

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC does not have Alcohol or Tea.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>573</ID>
      <DefaultText>Put the Mindeye on Aurigan without getting some alcohol first. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>574</ID>
      <DefaultText>You pull back Aurigan's long white hair and press the Mindeye to his skull, just behind his ear. The device adheres in a way you don't understand, for it secretes no glue or hooks, but it stays where it is placed. 

You turn it to the 'view' setting and speed it up.  Immediately he tenses and you can see his eyes moving behind his eyelids. His limbs start twitching too, and he begins murmuring under his breath.

A little while later, you hear Gurek return to his post outside the door, and you hide. He looks in on Aurigan, then backs out again when he sees him asleep. After that there are no intrusions for the rest of the night. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>575</ID>
      <DefaultText>Wait look around for some alcohol before putting the Mindeye on Aurigan. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>576</ID>
      <DefaultText>You search the room and find both a bottle of wine and some haffa juice. You could use either on him if you wanted.

As you approach him again, you see he is still fast asleep. 

{SCRIPT: Sets Has Alcohol Global.}
{SCRIPT: Sets Has Haffa Juice Global.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>577</ID>
      <DefaultText>You pull back Aurigan's long white hair and press the Mindeye to his skull, just behind his ear. The device adheres in a way you don't understand, for it secretes no glue or hooks, but it stays where it is placed. 

You turn it to the 'view' setting and speed it up.  Immediately Aurigan tenses and you can see his eyes moving behind his eyelids. His limbs start twitching too, and he begins murmuring under his breath.
</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>578</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stay with him and do nothing until it's time to take the Mindeye off again.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>579</ID>
      <DefaultText>Aurigan continues to twitch and mutter anxiously without ceasing, but he does not wake. 

A little while later, you hear Gurek return to his post outside the door, and you hide. The big man looks in on Aurigan, then backs out again when he sees him asleep. After that there are no intrusions for the rest of the night. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>580</ID>
      <DefaultText>Just as dawn begins to color the sky outside Aurigan's windows, the Mindeye chirps to indicate that it has shown him all the Nil's experiences. 

You peel it from behind his ear and sneak for the door, hoping that it worked, and that Gurek is asleep outside. A voice behind you turns you around. It's Aurigan.

"You little bitch," he says, sitting up in bed and glaring groggily at you. "That's right. I know what you did, and why you did it. It was all in what you showed me, what you tried to turn me into." He shudders. "By the makers, it took everything I had to maintain my *self* in that endless Nil nightmare."

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>581</ID>
      <DefaultText>He stands from the bed and steps toward you. "You'll be pleased to know that you achieved your goal. My father's Nil need never fear me again. You showed me that they too have hearts and minds. You however..." He raises burning eyes to yours. "The violation you subjected me to was worse than any crime I have ever committed. And you will pay for it - with your life."

As he pounces on you and drags you to the open window, the walls of his room blur into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. Aurigan and the pink sky and the Bore that yawns below you as he throws you out of the room all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>582</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stay with him and give him hourly doses of wine until it's time to take the Mindeye off again.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>583</ID>
      <DefaultText>Though you fear he might wake, you ease Aurigan onto his back and pull gently on his chin, opening his mouth. Thankfully, this does not jar him out of his immersive dream, and you are able to dribble a bit of wine into his mouth. He swallows it reflexively, then, after a minute his twitching lessens, and he seems to relax. 

A little while later, you hear Gurek return to his post outside the door, and you hide. The big man looks in on Aurigan, then backs out again when he sees him asleep. After that there are no intrusions for the rest of the night, and you are free to give him his wine every hour. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>584</ID>
      <DefaultText>Just as dawn begins to color the sky outside Aurigan's windows, the Mindeye chirps to indicate that it has shown him all the Nil's experiences. 

You peel it from behind his ear and sneak for the door, hoping that it worked, and that Gurek is asleep outside. A voice behind you turns you around. It's Aurigan.

"Wait," he says, sitting up in bed. "I... I know what you did and why you did it. It was all in what you showed me. I should be mad at your violation of my sovereign self and my free will, but... but you also showed that that is what I do to you and your kin every day."

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>585</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I promise you," he says. "That will change. I have spent too long thinking only *I* had a mind, only I knew pain. My father's Nil need never fear me again. And you..." He raises his eyes to yours. "Who risked all to teach me this, I will have you as my teacher, my guide in the ways of an enlightened life, and together we will find a way to free the Nil from their bondage. We make Haref a city of freedom and equality at last."

As he bows to you, the walls of his room blur into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. Aurigan and the pink sky beyond his windows all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>586</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I promise you," he says. "That will change. I have spent too long thinking only *I* had a mind, only I knew pain. My father's Nil need never fear me again. However..." He raises his eyes to yours. "I do not want you in his house any longer. It would be too strange. But know that you succeeded in changing me. Now go. I will ask my father to find you a good place."

As you bow to him, the walls of his room blur into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. Aurigan and the pink sky beyond his windows all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}

</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>587</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stay with him and dose him with strong tea until it's time to take the Mindeye off again.

{SCRIPT: Only plays if PC Has Tea.}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>588</ID>
      <DefaultText>Though you fear he might wake, you ease Aurigan over on his back and pull gently on his chin, opening his mouth. Thankfully, this does not jar him out of his immersive dream, and you are able to dribble a bit of tea into his mouth. He swallows it reflexively, and after a minute his twitching and moaning increases. He begins to whimper. 

A little while later, you hear Gurek return to his post outside the door, and you hide. He looks in on Aurigan, pauses as he sees him so restless, then shrugs and backs out again. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>589</ID>
      <DefaultText>After an hour you give Aurigan another few swallows of tea, and once again his agitation grows worse, until he sits up in his bed, screaming, "The Nil are in my head! The Nil are in my head!"

Before you can try to silence him, Gurek slams through the door and looks around. Aurigan points directly at you. "It was her! She put the Nil in my head! I have to get them out! I have to--"

He sceams again and snatches a dagger from his bedside table, then races for the door. Gurek tries to stop him but Aurigan dodges around him, then calls back to him. "This way! To the servant's quarters! We'll start there!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>590</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek heads after his master, then turns back and grabs you by the neck. "You don't deserve it," he rumbles. "But I'll give you the easy way out." And with that, he throws you out the window. 

You sail out into the night air with the stars and moons above you and the yawning black mouth of the Bore below, then begin to fall, speeding past gantries and catwalks and cables. 

As the starlight recedes above you, something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>591</ID>
      <DefaultText>Stay with him and dose him with haffa juice until it's time to take the Mindeye off again.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>592</ID>
      <DefaultText>Though you fear he might wake, you ease Aurigan onto his back and pull gently on his chin, opening his mouth. Thankfully, this does not jar him out of his immersive dream, and you are able to dribble a bit of haffa juice into his mouth. He swallows it reflexively, and after a minute his twitching and moaning increases. He begins to whimper. 

A little while later, you hear Gurek return to his post outside the door, and you hide. The big man looks in on Aurigan, pauses as he sees him so restless, then shrugs and backs out again. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>593</ID>
      <DefaultText>After an hour you give Aurigan another few swallows of haffa juice, and once again his agitation grows worse, until at last he sits up in his bed, screaming, "The Nil are in my head! The Nil are in my head!"

Before you can try to silence him, Gurek slams through the door and looks around. Aurigan points directly at you. "It was her! She put the Nil in my head! I have to get them out! I have to--"

He sceams again and snatches a dagger from his bedside table, then races for the door. Gurek tries to stop him but Aurigan dodges around him, then calls back to him. "This way! To the servant's quarters! We'll start there!"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>595</ID>
      <DefaultText>Decide to forget that Aurigan had an innocent Nil murdered, and do nothing. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>596</ID>
      <DefaultText>As you make up your mind to do nothing, the walls around you blur into a red haze, and something that feels like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. The library, the sunshine, the chirping of the moth, all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>597</ID>
      <DefaultText>"What are shin men?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>598</ID>
      <DefaultText>"Moneylenders. They make loans to suckers like the boss. And if you can't pay 'em back, they break your toes, then work their way up from there. I have to chase 'em away from the house almost every night. One night they're gonna get in."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>599</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek hesitates, torn between dealing with you or going after his master, finally, he turns and runs out the door. 

As you watch him go, the walls of Aurigan's room blur into a red haze, and something like a hot fist clenches your guts and wrenches you bodily out of the world. Aurigan's bed and the pink sky beyond his windows all vanish into silent darkness. 

{MERE ENDS}</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>600</ID>
      <DefaultText>Shelve the books. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>601</ID>
      <DefaultText>You don't know the library's filing system, but as you explore the shelves you find that it's simple enough, and you return all the books to their proper places in a few moments.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>602</ID>
      <DefaultText>Use Aurigan's desperate situation as the basis for a suicide note. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>603</ID>
      <DefaultText>You already seem well versed in mimicking Aurigan's handwriting and signature, so it only takes you a few tries before you have what you feel is an acceptable suicide note. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>604</ID>
      <DefaultText>It reads...

Dear father, 

The shame of my debts has become too much. I can bear it no more. Farewell.

Your son, 

Aurigan</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>605</ID>
      <DefaultText>You pause as you realize that placing the Mindeye on the singing moth will erase the week in the life of a Nil that is already recorded in it, and it will no longer be possible to try to make Aurigan more empathetic. </DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>606</ID>
      <DefaultText>Place the Mindeye on the singing moth anyway.</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>608</ID>
      <DefaultText>Gurek looks up at your approach. "How's your scheme coming, Nil?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>609</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I've put the Mindeye on the moth. It will record everything that happens  in the library. If you tell Aurigan the Diary of Eosus will free him from debt, the moth will catch him stealing it, and I will bring the proof to Veresterios."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>610</ID>
      <DefaultText>"I regret to inform you, sirs, that the Diary of Eosus is missing, perhaps stolen. I might, however, know a way to expose the thief."</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
    <Entry>
      <ID>611</ID>
      <DefaultText>The two Sona are discussing a newly acquired book as you approach and wait. 

Finally Veresterios looks up. "Yes, Mer. What is it?"</DefaultText>
      <FemaleText />
    </Entry>
